11510 void Sema::CheckFreeArguments(const CallExpr *E) {
11511  const std::string CalleeName =
11512  cast<FunctionDecl>(E->getCalleeDecl())->getQualifiedNameAsString();
11513 
11514  { // Prefer something that doesn't involve a cast to make things simpler.
11515  const Expr *Arg = E->getArg(0)->IgnoreParenCasts();
11516  if (const auto *UnaryExpr = dyn_cast<UnaryOperator>(Arg))
11517  switch (UnaryExpr->getOpcode()) {
11518  case UnaryOperator::Opcode::UO_AddrOf:
11519  return CheckFreeArgumentsAddressof(*this, CalleeName, UnaryExpr);
11520  case UnaryOperator::Opcode::UO_Plus:
11521  return CheckFreeArgumentsPlus(*this, CalleeName, UnaryExpr);
11522  default:
11523  break;
11524  }
11525 
11526  if (const auto *Lvalue = dyn_cast<DeclRefExpr>(Arg))
11527  if (Lvalue->getType()->isArrayType())
11528  return CheckFreeArgumentsStackArray(*this, CalleeName, Lvalue);
11529 
11530  if (const auto *Label = dyn_cast<AddrLabelExpr>(Arg)) {
11531  Diag(Label->getBeginLoc(), diag::warn_free_nonheap_object)
11532  << CalleeName << 0 /*object: */ << Label->getLabel()->getIdentifier();
11533  return;
11534  }
11535 
11536  if (isa<BlockExpr>(Arg)) {
11537  Diag(Arg->getBeginLoc(), diag::warn_free_nonheap_object)
11538  << CalleeName << 1 /*object: block*/;
11539  return;
11540  }
11541  }
11542  // Maybe the cast was important, check after the other cases.
11543  if (const auto *Cast = dyn_cast<CastExpr>(E->getArg(0)))
11544  return CheckFreeArgumentsCast(*this, CalleeName, Cast);
11545 }
11546 
11547 void
11548 Sema::CheckReturnValExpr(Expr *RetValExp, QualType lhsType,
11549  SourceLocation ReturnLoc,
11550  bool isObjCMethod,
11551  const AttrVec *Attrs,
11552  const FunctionDecl *FD) {
11553  // Check if the return value is null but should not be.
11554  if (((Attrs && hasSpecificAttr<ReturnsNonNullAttr>(*Attrs)) ||
11555  (!isObjCMethod && isNonNullType(Context, lhsType))) &&
11556  CheckNonNullExpr(*this, RetValExp))
11557  Diag(ReturnLoc, diag::warn_null_ret)
11558  << (isObjCMethod ? 1 : 0) << RetValExp->getSourceRange();
11559 
11560  // C++11 [basic.stc.dynamic.allocation]p4:
11561  // If an allocation function declared with a non-throwing
11562  // exception-specification fails to allocate storage, it shall return
11563  // a null pointer. Any other allocation function that fails to allocate
11564  // storage shall indicate failure only by throwing an exception [...]
11565  if (FD) {
11566  OverloadedOperatorKind Op = FD->getOverloadedOperator();
11567  if (Op == OO_New || Op == OO_Array_New) {
11568  const FunctionProtoType *Proto
11569  = FD->getType()->castAs<FunctionProtoType>();
11570  if (!Proto->isNothrow(/*ResultIfDependent*/true) &&
11571  CheckNonNullExpr(*this, RetValExp))
11572  Diag(ReturnLoc, diag::warn_operator_new_returns_null)
11573  << FD << getLangOpts().CPlusPlus11;
11574  }
11575  }
11576 
11577  // PPC MMA non-pointer types are not allowed as return type. Checking the type
11578  // here prevent the user from using a PPC MMA type as trailing return type.
11579  if (Context.getTargetInfo().getTriple().isPPC64())
11580  CheckPPCMMAType(RetValExp->getType(), ReturnLoc);
11581 }
11582 
11583 /// Check for comparisons of floating-point values using == and !=. Issue a
11584 /// warning if the comparison is not likely to do what the programmer intended.
11585 void Sema::CheckFloatComparison(SourceLocation Loc, Expr *LHS, Expr *RHS,
11586  BinaryOperatorKind Opcode) {
11587  // Match and capture subexpressions such as "(float) X == 0.1".
11588  FloatingLiteral *FPLiteral;
11589  CastExpr *FPCast;
11590  auto getCastAndLiteral = [&FPLiteral, &FPCast](Expr *L, Expr *R) {
11591  FPLiteral = dyn_cast<FloatingLiteral>(L->IgnoreParens());
11592  FPCast = dyn_cast<CastExpr>(R->IgnoreParens());
11593  return FPLiteral && FPCast;
11594  };
11595 
11596  if (getCastAndLiteral(LHS, RHS) || getCastAndLiteral(RHS, LHS)) {
11597  auto *SourceTy = FPCast->getSubExpr()->getType()->getAs<BuiltinType>();
11598  auto *TargetTy = FPLiteral->getType()->getAs<BuiltinType>();
11599  if (SourceTy && TargetTy && SourceTy->isFloatingPoint() &&
11600  TargetTy->isFloatingPoint()) {
11601  bool Lossy;
11602  llvm::APFloat TargetC = FPLiteral->getValue();
11603  TargetC.convert(Context.getFloatTypeSemantics(QualType(SourceTy, 0)),
11604  llvm::APFloat::rmNearestTiesToEven, &Lossy);
11605  if (Lossy) {
11606  // If the literal cannot be represented in the source type, then a
11607  // check for == is always false and check for != is always true.
11608  Diag(Loc, diag::warn_float_compare_literal)
11609  << (Opcode == BO_EQ) << QualType(SourceTy, 0)
11610  << LHS->getSourceRange() << RHS->getSourceRange();
11611  return;
11612  }
11613  }
11614  }
11615 
11616  // Match a more general floating-point equality comparison (-Wfloat-equal).
11617  Expr* LeftExprSansParen = LHS->IgnoreParenImpCasts();
11618  Expr* RightExprSansParen = RHS->IgnoreParenImpCasts();
11619 
11620  // Special case: check for x == x (which is OK).
11621  // Do not emit warnings for such cases.
11622  if (DeclRefExpr* DRL = dyn_cast<DeclRefExpr>(LeftExprSansParen))
11623  if (DeclRefExpr* DRR = dyn_cast<DeclRefExpr>(RightExprSansParen))
11624  if (DRL->getDecl() == DRR->getDecl())
11625  return;
11626 
11627  // Special case: check for comparisons against literals that can be exactly
11628  // represented by APFloat. In such cases, do not emit a warning. This
11629  // is a heuristic: often comparison against such literals are used to
11630  // detect if a value in a variable has not changed. This clearly can
11631  // lead to false negatives.
11632  if (FloatingLiteral* FLL = dyn_cast<FloatingLiteral>(LeftExprSansParen)) {
11633  if (FLL->isExact())
11634  return;
11635  } else
11636  if (FloatingLiteral* FLR = dyn_cast<FloatingLiteral>(RightExprSansParen))
11637  if (FLR->isExact())
11638  return;
11639 
11640  // Check for comparisons with builtin types.
11641  if (CallExpr* CL = dyn_cast<CallExpr>(LeftExprSansParen))
11642  if (CL->getBuiltinCallee())
11643  return;
11644 
11645  if (CallExpr* CR = dyn_cast<CallExpr>(RightExprSansParen))
11646  if (CR->getBuiltinCallee())
11647  return;
11648 
11649  // Emit the diagnostic.
11650  Diag(Loc, diag::warn_floatingpoint_eq)
11651  << LHS->getSourceRange() << RHS->getSourceRange();
11652 }
11653 
11654 //===--- CHECK: Integer mixed-sign comparisons (-Wsign-compare) --------===//
11655 //===--- CHECK: Lossy implicit conversions (-Wconversion) --------------===//
11656 
11657 namespace {
11658 
11659 /// Structure recording the 'active' range of an integer-valued
11660 /// expression.
11661 struct IntRange {
11662  /// The number of bits active in the int. Note that this includes exactly one
11663  /// sign bit if !NonNegative.
11664  unsigned Width;
11665 
11666  /// True if the int is known not to have negative values. If so, all leading
11667  /// bits before Width are known zero, otherwise they are known to be the
11668  /// same as the MSB within Width.
11669  bool NonNegative;
11670 
11671  IntRange(unsigned Width, bool NonNegative)
11672  : Width(Width), NonNegative(NonNegative) {}
11673 
11674  /// Number of bits excluding the sign bit.
11675  unsigned valueBits() const {
11676  return NonNegative ? Width : Width - 1;
11677  }
11678 
11679  /// Returns the range of the bool type.
11680  static IntRange forBoolType() {
11681  return IntRange(1, true);
11682  }
11683 
11684  /// Returns the range of an opaque value of the given integral type.
11685  static IntRange forValueOfType(ASTContext &C, QualType T) {
11686  return forValueOfCanonicalType(C,
11687  T->getCanonicalTypeInternal().getTypePtr());
11688  }
11689 
11690  /// Returns the range of an opaque value of a canonical integral type.
11691  static IntRange forValueOfCanonicalType(ASTContext &C, const Type *T) {
11692  assert(T->isCanonicalUnqualified());
11693 
11694  if (const VectorType *VT = dyn_cast<VectorType>(T))
11695  T = VT->getElementType().getTypePtr();
11696  if (const ComplexType *CT = dyn_cast<ComplexType>(T))
11697  T = CT->getElementType().getTypePtr();
11698  if (const AtomicType *AT = dyn_cast<AtomicType>(T))
11699  T = AT->getValueType().getTypePtr();
11700 
11701  if (!C.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus) {
11702  // For enum types in C code, use the underlying datatype.
11703  if (const EnumType *ET = dyn_cast<EnumType>(T))
11704  T = ET->getDecl()->getIntegerType().getDesugaredType(C).getTypePtr();
11705  } else if (const EnumType *ET = dyn_cast<EnumType>(T)) {
11706  // For enum types in C++, use the known bit width of the enumerators.
11707  EnumDecl *Enum = ET->getDecl();
11708  // In C++11, enums can have a fixed underlying type. Use this type to
11709  // compute the range.
11710  if (Enum->isFixed()) {
11711  return IntRange(C.getIntWidth(QualType(T, 0)),
11712  !ET->isSignedIntegerOrEnumerationType());
11713  }
11714 
11715  unsigned NumPositive = Enum->getNumPositiveBits();
11716  unsigned NumNegative = Enum->getNumNegativeBits();
11717 
11718  if (NumNegative == 0)
11719  return IntRange(NumPositive, true/*NonNegative*/);
11720  else
11721  return IntRange(std::max(NumPositive + 1, NumNegative),
11722  false/*NonNegative*/);
11723  }
11724 
11725  if (const auto *EIT = dyn_cast<BitIntType>(T))
11726  return IntRange(EIT->getNumBits(), EIT->isUnsigned());
11727 
11728  const BuiltinType *BT = cast<BuiltinType>(T);
11729  assert(BT->isInteger());
11730 
11731  return IntRange(C.getIntWidth(QualType(T, 0)), BT->isUnsignedInteger());
11732  }
11733 
11734  /// Returns the "target" range of a canonical integral type, i.e.
11735  /// the range of values expressible in the type.
11736  ///
11737  /// This matches forValueOfCanonicalType except that enums have the
11738  /// full range of their type, not the range of their enumerators.
11739  static IntRange forTargetOfCanonicalType(ASTContext &C, const Type *T) {
11740  assert(T->isCanonicalUnqualified());
11741 
11742  if (const VectorType *VT = dyn_cast<VectorType>(T))
11743  T = VT->getElementType().getTypePtr();
11744  if (const ComplexType *CT = dyn_cast<ComplexType>(T))
11745  T = CT->getElementType().getTypePtr();
11746  if (const AtomicType *AT = dyn_cast<AtomicType>(T))
11747  T = AT->getValueType().getTypePtr();
11748  if (const EnumType *ET = dyn_cast<EnumType>(T))
11749  T = C.getCanonicalType(ET->getDecl()->getIntegerType()).getTypePtr();
11750 
11751  if (const auto *EIT = dyn_cast<BitIntType>(T))
11752  return IntRange(EIT->getNumBits(), EIT->isUnsigned());
11753 
11754  const BuiltinType *BT = cast<BuiltinType>(T);
11755  assert(BT->isInteger());
11756 
11757  return IntRange(C.getIntWidth(QualType(T, 0)), BT->isUnsignedInteger());
11758  }
11759 
11760  /// Returns the supremum of two ranges: i.e. their conservative merge.
11761  static IntRange join(IntRange L, IntRange R) {
11762  bool Unsigned = L.NonNegative && R.NonNegative;
11763  return IntRange(std::max(L.valueBits(), R.valueBits()) + !Unsigned,
11764  L.NonNegative && R.NonNegative);
11765  }
11766 
11767  /// Return the range of a bitwise-AND of the two ranges.
11768  static IntRange bit_and(IntRange L, IntRange R) {
11769  unsigned Bits = std::max(L.Width, R.Width);
11770  bool NonNegative = false;
11771  if (L.NonNegative) {
11772  Bits = std::min(Bits, L.Width);
11773  NonNegative = true;
11774  }
11775  if (R.NonNegative) {
11776  Bits = std::min(Bits, R.Width);
11777  NonNegative = true;
11778  }
11779  return IntRange(Bits, NonNegative);
11780  }
11781 
11782  /// Return the range of a sum of the two ranges.
11783  static IntRange sum(IntRange L, IntRange R) {
11784  bool Unsigned = L.NonNegative && R.NonNegative;
11785  return IntRange(std::max(L.valueBits(), R.valueBits()) + 1 + !Unsigned,
11786  Unsigned);
11787  }
11788 
11789  /// Return the range of a difference of the two ranges.
11790  static IntRange difference(IntRange L, IntRange R) {
11791  // We need a 1-bit-wider range if:
11792  // 1) LHS can be negative: least value can be reduced.
11793  // 2) RHS can be negative: greatest value can be increased.
11794  bool CanWiden = !L.NonNegative || !R.NonNegative;
11795  bool Unsigned = L.NonNegative && R.Width == 0;
11796  return IntRange(std::max(L.valueBits(), R.valueBits()) + CanWiden +
11797  !Unsigned,
11798  Unsigned);
11799  }
11800 
11801  /// Return the range of a product of the two ranges.
11802  static IntRange product(IntRange L, IntRange R) {
11803  // If both LHS and RHS can be negative, we can form
11804  // -2^L * -2^R = 2^(L + R)
11805  // which requires L + R + 1 value bits to represent.
11806  bool CanWiden = !L.NonNegative && !R.NonNegative;
11807  bool Unsigned = L.NonNegative && R.NonNegative;
11808  return IntRange(L.valueBits() + R.valueBits() + CanWiden + !Unsigned,
11809  Unsigned);
11810  }
11811 
11812  /// Return the range of a remainder operation between the two ranges.
11813  static IntRange rem(IntRange L, IntRange R) {
11814  // The result of a remainder can't be larger than the result of
11815  // either side. The sign of the result is the sign of the LHS.
11816  bool Unsigned = L.NonNegative;
11817  return IntRange(std::min(L.valueBits(), R.valueBits()) + !Unsigned,
11818  Unsigned);
11819  }
11820 };
11821 
11822 } // namespace
11823 
11824 static IntRange GetValueRange(ASTContext &C, llvm::APSInt &value,
11825  unsigned MaxWidth) {
11826  if (value.isSigned() && value.isNegative())
11827  return IntRange(value.getMinSignedBits(), false);
11828 
11829  if (value.getBitWidth() > MaxWidth)
11830  value = value.trunc(MaxWidth);
11831 
11832  // isNonNegative() just checks the sign bit without considering
11833  // signedness.
11834  return IntRange(value.getActiveBits(), true);
11835 }
11836 
11837 static IntRange GetValueRange(ASTContext &C, APValue &result, QualType Ty,
11838  unsigned MaxWidth) {
11839  if (result.isInt())
11840  return GetValueRange(C, result.getInt(), MaxWidth);
11841 
11842  if (result.isVector()) {
11843  IntRange R = GetValueRange(C, result.getVectorElt(0), Ty, MaxWidth);
11844  for (unsigned i = 1, e = result.getVectorLength(); i != e; ++i) {
11845  IntRange El = GetValueRange(C, result.getVectorElt(i), Ty, MaxWidth);
11846  R = IntRange::join(R, El);
11847  }
11848  return R;
11849  }
11850 
11851  if (result.isComplexInt()) {
11852  IntRange R = GetValueRange(C, result.getComplexIntReal(), MaxWidth);
11853  IntRange I = GetValueRange(C, result.getComplexIntImag(), MaxWidth);
11854  return IntRange::join(R, I);
11855  }
11856 
11857  // This can happen with lossless casts to intptr_t of "based" lvalues.
11858  // Assume it might use arbitrary bits.
11859  // FIXME: The only reason we need to pass the type in here is to get
11860  // the sign right on this one case. It would be nice if APValue
11861  // preserved this.
11862  assert(result.isLValue() || result.isAddrLabelDiff());
11863  return IntRange(MaxWidth, Ty->isUnsignedIntegerOrEnumerationType());
11864 }
11865 
11866 static QualType GetExprType(const Expr *E) {
11867  QualType Ty = E->getType();
11868  if (const AtomicType *AtomicRHS = Ty->getAs<AtomicType>())
11869  Ty = AtomicRHS->getValueType();
11870  return Ty;
11871 }
11872 
11873 /// Pseudo-evaluate the given integer expression, estimating the
11874 /// range of values it might take.
11875 ///
11876 /// \param MaxWidth The width to which the value will be truncated.
11877 /// \param Approximate If \c true, return a likely range for the result: in
11878 /// particular, assume that arithmetic on narrower types doesn't leave
11879 /// those types. If \c false, return a range including all possible
11880 /// result values.
11881 static IntRange GetExprRange(ASTContext &C, const Expr *E, unsigned MaxWidth,
11882  bool InConstantContext, bool Approximate) {
11883  E = E->IgnoreParens();
11884 
11885  // Try a full evaluation first.
11886  Expr::EvalResult result;
11887  if (E->EvaluateAsRValue(result, C, InConstantContext))
11888  return GetValueRange(C, result.Val, GetExprType(E), MaxWidth);
11889 
11890  // I think we only want to look through implicit casts here; if the
11891  // user has an explicit widening cast, we should treat the value as
11892  // being of the new, wider type.
11893  if (const auto *CE = dyn_cast<ImplicitCastExpr>(E)) {
11894  if (CE->getCastKind() == CK_NoOp || CE->getCastKind() == CK_LValueToRValue)
11895  return GetExprRange(C, CE->getSubExpr(), MaxWidth, InConstantContext,
11896  Approximate);
11897 
11898  IntRange OutputTypeRange = IntRange::forValueOfType(C, GetExprType(CE));
11899 
11900  bool isIntegerCast = CE->getCastKind() == CK_IntegralCast ||
11901  CE->getCastKind() == CK_BooleanToSignedIntegral;
11902 
11903  // Assume that non-integer casts can span the full range of the type.
11904  if (!isIntegerCast)
11905  return OutputTypeRange;
11906 
11907  IntRange SubRange = GetExprRange(C, CE->getSubExpr(),
11908  std::min(MaxWidth, OutputTypeRange.Width),
11909  InConstantContext, Approximate);
11910 
11911  // Bail out if the subexpr's range is as wide as the cast type.
11912  if (SubRange.Width >= OutputTypeRange.Width)
11913  return OutputTypeRange;
11914 
11915  // Otherwise, we take the smaller width, and we're non-negative if
11916  // either the output type or the subexpr is.
11917  return IntRange(SubRange.Width,
11918  SubRange.NonNegative || OutputTypeRange.NonNegative);
11919  }
11920 
11921  if (const auto *CO = dyn_cast<ConditionalOperator>(E)) {
11922  // If we can fold the condition, just take that operand.
11923  bool CondResult;
11924  if (CO->getCond()->EvaluateAsBooleanCondition(CondResult, C))
11925  return GetExprRange(C,
11926  CondResult ? CO->getTrueExpr() : CO->getFalseExpr(),
11927  MaxWidth, InConstantContext, Approximate);
11928 
11929  // Otherwise, conservatively merge.
11930  // GetExprRange requires an integer expression, but a throw expression
11931  // results in a void type.
11932  Expr *E = CO->getTrueExpr();
11933  IntRange L = E->getType()->isVoidType()
11934  ? IntRange{0, true}
11935  : GetExprRange(C, E, MaxWidth, InConstantContext, Approximate);
11936  E = CO->getFalseExpr();
11937  IntRange R = E->getType()->isVoidType()
11938  ? IntRange{0, true}
11939  : GetExprRange(C, E, MaxWidth, InConstantContext, Approximate);
11940  return IntRange::join(L, R);
11941  }
11942 
11943  if (const auto *BO = dyn_cast<BinaryOperator>(E)) {
11944  IntRange (*Combine)(IntRange, IntRange) = IntRange::join;
11945 
11946  switch (BO->getOpcode()) {
11947  case BO_Cmp:
11948  llvm_unreachable("builtin <=> should have class type");
11949 
11950  // Boolean-valued operations are single-bit and positive.
11951  case BO_LAnd:
11952  case BO_LOr:
11953  case BO_LT:
11954  case BO_GT:
11955  case BO_LE:
11956  case BO_GE:
11957  case BO_EQ:
11958  case BO_NE:
11959  return IntRange::forBoolType();
11960 
11961  // The type of the assignments is the type of the LHS, so the RHS
11962  // is not necessarily the same type.
11963  case BO_MulAssign:
11964  case BO_DivAssign:
11965  case BO_RemAssign:
11966  case BO_AddAssign:
11967  case BO_SubAssign:
11968  case BO_XorAssign:
11969  case BO_OrAssign:
11970  // TODO: bitfields?
11971  return IntRange::forValueOfType(C, GetExprType(E));
11972 
11973  // Simple assignments just pass through the RHS, which will have
11974  // been coerced to the LHS type.
11975  case BO_Assign:
11976  // TODO: bitfields?
11977  return GetExprRange(C, BO->getRHS(), MaxWidth, InConstantContext,
11978  Approximate);
11979 
11980  // Operations with opaque sources are black-listed.
11981  case BO_PtrMemD:
11982  case BO_PtrMemI:
11983  return IntRange::forValueOfType(C, GetExprType(E));
11984 
11985  // Bitwise-and uses the *infinum* of the two source ranges.
11986  case BO_And:
11987  case BO_AndAssign:
11988  Combine = IntRange::bit_and;
11989  break;
11990 
11991  // Left shift gets black-listed based on a judgement call.
11992  case BO_Shl:
11993  // ...except that we want to treat '1 << (blah)' as logically
11994  // positive. It's an important idiom.
11995  if (IntegerLiteral *I
11996  = dyn_cast<IntegerLiteral>(BO->getLHS()->IgnoreParenCasts())) {
11997  if (I->getValue() == 1) {
11998  IntRange R = IntRange::forValueOfType(C, GetExprType(E));
11999  return IntRange(R.Width, /*NonNegative*/ true);
12000  }
12001  }
12002  LLVM_FALLTHROUGH;
12003 
12004  case BO_ShlAssign:
12005  return IntRange::forValueOfType(C, GetExprType(E));
12006 
12007  // Right shift by a constant can narrow its left argument.
12008  case BO_Shr:
12009  case BO_ShrAssign: {
12010  IntRange L = GetExprRange(C, BO->getLHS(), MaxWidth, InConstantContext,
12011  Approximate);
12012 
12013  // If the shift amount is a positive constant, drop the width by
12014  // that much.
12015  if (Optional<llvm::APSInt> shift =
12016  BO->getRHS()->getIntegerConstantExpr(C)) {
12017  if (shift->isNonNegative()) {
12018  unsigned zext = shift->getZExtValue();
12019  if (zext >= L.Width)
12020  L.Width = (L.NonNegative ? 0 : 1);
12021  else
12022  L.Width -= zext;
12023  }
12024  }
12025 
12026  return L;
12027  }
12028 
12029  // Comma acts as its right operand.
12030  case BO_Comma:
12031  return GetExprRange(C, BO->getRHS(), MaxWidth, InConstantContext,
12032  Approximate);
12033 
12034  case BO_Add:
12035  if (!Approximate)
12036  Combine = IntRange::sum;
12037  break;
12038 
12039  case BO_Sub:
12040  if (BO->getLHS()->getType()->isPointerType())
12041  return IntRange::forValueOfType(C, GetExprType(E));
12042  if (!Approximate)
12043  Combine = IntRange::difference;
12044  break;
12045 
12046  case BO_Mul:
12047  if (!Approximate)
12048  Combine = IntRange::product;
12049  break;
12050 
12051  // The width of a division result is mostly determined by the size
12052  // of the LHS.
12053  case BO_Div: {
12054  // Don't 'pre-truncate' the operands.
12055  unsigned opWidth = C.getIntWidth(GetExprType(E));
12056  IntRange L = GetExprRange(C, BO->getLHS(), opWidth, InConstantContext,
12057  Approximate);
12058 
12059  // If the divisor is constant, use that.
12060  if (Optional<llvm::APSInt> divisor =
12061  BO->getRHS()->getIntegerConstantExpr(C)) {
12062  unsigned log2 = divisor->logBase2(); // floor(log_2(divisor))
12063  if (log2 >= L.Width)
12064  L.Width = (L.NonNegative ? 0 : 1);
12065  else
12066  L.Width = std::min(L.Width - log2, MaxWidth);
12067  return L;
12068  }
12069 
12070  // Otherwise, just use the LHS's width.
12071  // FIXME: This is wrong if the LHS could be its minimal value and the RHS
12072  // could be -1.
12073  IntRange R = GetExprRange(C, BO->getRHS(), opWidth, InConstantContext,
12074  Approximate);
12075  return IntRange(L.Width, L.NonNegative && R.NonNegative);
12076  }
12077 
12078  case BO_Rem:
12079  Combine = IntRange::rem;
12080  break;
12081 
12082  // The default behavior is okay for these.
12083  case BO_Xor:
12084  case BO_Or:
12085  break;
12086  }
12087 
12088  // Combine the two ranges, but limit the result to the type in which we
12089  // performed the computation.
12090  QualType T = GetExprType(E);
12091  unsigned opWidth = C.getIntWidth(T);
12092  IntRange L =
12093  GetExprRange(C, BO->getLHS(), opWidth, InConstantContext, Approximate);
12094  IntRange R =
12095  GetExprRange(C, BO->getRHS(), opWidth, InConstantContext, Approximate);
12096  IntRange C = Combine(L, R);
12097  C.NonNegative |= T->isUnsignedIntegerOrEnumerationType();
12098  C.Width = std::min(C.Width, MaxWidth);
12099  return C;
12100  }
12101 
12102  if (const auto *UO = dyn_cast<UnaryOperator>(E)) {
12103  switch (UO->getOpcode()) {
12104  // Boolean-valued operations are white-listed.
12105  case UO_LNot:
12106  return IntRange::forBoolType();
12107 
12108  // Operations with opaque sources are black-listed.
12109  case UO_Deref:
12110  case UO_AddrOf: // should be impossible
12111  return IntRange::forValueOfType(C, GetExprType(E));
12112 
12113  default:
12114  return GetExprRange(C, UO->getSubExpr(), MaxWidth, InConstantContext,
12115  Approximate);
12116  }
12117  }
12118 
12119  if (const auto *OVE = dyn_cast<OpaqueValueExpr>(E))
12120  return GetExprRange(C, OVE->getSourceExpr(), MaxWidth, InConstantContext,
12121  Approximate);
12122 
12123  if (const auto *BitField = E->getSourceBitField())
12124  return IntRange(BitField->getBitWidthValue(C),
12125  BitField->getType()->isUnsignedIntegerOrEnumerationType());
12126 
12127  return IntRange::forValueOfType(C, GetExprType(E));
12128 }
12129 
12130 static IntRange GetExprRange(ASTContext &C, const Expr *E,
12131  bool InConstantContext, bool Approximate) {
12132  return GetExprRange(C, E, C.getIntWidth(GetExprType(E)), InConstantContext,
12133  Approximate);
12134 }
12135 
12136 /// Checks whether the given value, which currently has the given
12137 /// source semantics, has the same value when coerced through the
12138 /// target semantics.
12139 static bool IsSameFloatAfterCast(const llvm::APFloat &value,
12140  const llvm::fltSemantics &Src,
12141  const llvm::fltSemantics &Tgt) {
12142  llvm::APFloat truncated = value;
12143 
12144  bool ignored;
12145  truncated.convert(Src, llvm::APFloat::rmNearestTiesToEven, &ignored);
12146  truncated.convert(Tgt, llvm::APFloat::rmNearestTiesToEven, &ignored);
12147 
12148  return truncated.bitwiseIsEqual(value);
12149 }
12150 
12151 /// Checks whether the given value, which currently has the given
12152 /// source semantics, has the same value when coerced through the
12153 /// target semantics.
12154 ///
12155 /// The value might be a vector of floats (or a complex number).
12156 static bool IsSameFloatAfterCast(const APValue &value,
12157  const llvm::fltSemantics &Src,
12158  const llvm::fltSemantics &Tgt) {
12159  if (value.isFloat())
12160  return IsSameFloatAfterCast(value.getFloat(), Src, Tgt);
12161 
12162  if (value.isVector()) {
12163  for (unsigned i = 0, e = value.getVectorLength(); i != e; ++i)
12164  if (!IsSameFloatAfterCast(value.getVectorElt(i), Src, Tgt))
12165  return false;
12166  return true;
12167  }
12168 
12169  assert(value.isComplexFloat());
12170  return (IsSameFloatAfterCast(value.getComplexFloatReal(), Src, Tgt) &&
12171  IsSameFloatAfterCast(value.getComplexFloatImag(), Src, Tgt));
12172 }
12173 
12174 static void AnalyzeImplicitConversions(Sema &S, Expr *E, SourceLocation CC,
12175  bool IsListInit = false);
12176 
12177 static bool IsEnumConstOrFromMacro(Sema &S, Expr *E) {
12178  // Suppress cases where we are comparing against an enum constant.
12179  if (const DeclRefExpr *DR =
12180  dyn_cast<DeclRefExpr>(E->IgnoreParenImpCasts()))
12181  if (isa<EnumConstantDecl>(DR->getDecl()))
12182  return true;
12183 
12184  // Suppress cases where the value is expanded from a macro, unless that macro
12185  // is how a language represents a boolean literal. This is the case in both C
12186  // and Objective-C.
12187  SourceLocation BeginLoc = E->getBeginLoc();
12188  if (BeginLoc.isMacroID()) {
12189  StringRef MacroName = Lexer::getImmediateMacroName(
12190  BeginLoc, S.getSourceManager(), S.getLangOpts());
12191  return MacroName != "YES" && MacroName != "NO" &&
12192  MacroName != "true" && MacroName != "false";
12193  }
12194 
12195  return false;
12196 }
12197 
12198 static bool isKnownToHaveUnsignedValue(Expr *E) {
12199  return E->getType()->isIntegerType() &&
12200  (!E->getType()->isSignedIntegerType() ||
12201  !E->IgnoreParenImpCasts()->getType()->isSignedIntegerType());
12202 }
12203 
12204 namespace {
12205 /// The promoted range of values of a type. In general this has the
12206 /// following structure:
12207 ///
12208 /// |-----------| . . . |-----------|
12209 /// ^ ^ ^ ^
12210 /// Min HoleMin HoleMax Max
12211 ///
12212 /// ... where there is only a hole if a signed type is promoted to unsigned
12213 /// (in which case Min and Max are the smallest and largest representable
12214 /// values).
12215 struct PromotedRange {
12216  // Min, or HoleMax if there is a hole.
12217  llvm::APSInt PromotedMin;
12218  // Max, or HoleMin if there is a hole.
12219  llvm::APSInt PromotedMax;
12220 
12221  PromotedRange(IntRange R, unsigned BitWidth, bool Unsigned) {
12222  if (R.Width == 0)
12223  PromotedMin = PromotedMax = llvm::APSInt(BitWidth, Unsigned);
12224  else if (R.Width >= BitWidth && !Unsigned) {
12225  // Promotion made the type *narrower*. This happens when promoting
12226  // a < 32-bit unsigned / <= 32-bit signed bit-field to 'signed int'.
12227  // Treat all values of 'signed int' as being in range for now.
12228  PromotedMin = llvm::APSInt::getMinValue(BitWidth, Unsigned);
12229  PromotedMax = llvm::APSInt::getMaxValue(BitWidth, Unsigned);
12230  } else {
12231  PromotedMin = llvm::APSInt::getMinValue(R.Width, R.NonNegative)
12232  .extOrTrunc(BitWidth);
12233  PromotedMin.setIsUnsigned(Unsigned);
12234 
12235  PromotedMax = llvm::APSInt::getMaxValue(R.Width, R.NonNegative)
12236  .extOrTrunc(BitWidth);
12237  PromotedMax.setIsUnsigned(Unsigned);
12238  }
12239  }
12240 
12241  // Determine whether this range is contiguous (has no hole).
12242  bool isContiguous() const { return PromotedMin <= PromotedMax; }
12243 
12244  // Where a constant value is within the range.
12245  enum ComparisonResult {
12246  LT = 0x1,
12247  LE = 0x2,
12248  GT = 0x4,
12249  GE = 0x8,
12250  EQ = 0x10,
12251  NE = 0x20,
12252  InRangeFlag = 0x40,
12253 
12254  Less = LE | LT | NE,
12255  Min = LE | InRangeFlag,
12256  InRange = InRangeFlag,
12257  Max = GE | InRangeFlag,
12258  Greater = GE | GT | NE,
12259 
12260  OnlyValue = LE | GE | EQ | InRangeFlag,
12261  InHole = NE
12262  };
12263 
12264  ComparisonResult compare(const llvm::APSInt &Value) const {
12265  assert(Value.getBitWidth() == PromotedMin.getBitWidth() &&
12266  Value.isUnsigned() == PromotedMin.isUnsigned());
12267  if (!isContiguous()) {
12268  assert(Value.isUnsigned() && "discontiguous range for signed compare");
12269  if (Value.isMinValue()) return Min;
12270  if (Value.isMaxValue()) return Max;
12271  if (Value >= PromotedMin) return InRange;
12272  if (Value <= PromotedMax) return InRange;
12273  return InHole;
12274  }
12275 
12276  switch (llvm::APSInt::compareValues(Value, PromotedMin)) {
12277  case -1: return Less;
12278  case 0: return PromotedMin == PromotedMax ? OnlyValue : Min;
12279  case 1:
12280  switch (llvm::APSInt::compareValues(Value, PromotedMax)) {
12281  case -1: return InRange;
12282  case 0: return Max;
12283  case 1: return Greater;
12284  }
12285  }
12286 
12287  llvm_unreachable("impossible compare result");
12288  }
12289 
12290  static llvm::Optional<StringRef>
12291  constantValue(BinaryOperatorKind Op, ComparisonResult R, bool ConstantOnRHS) {
12292  if (Op == BO_Cmp) {
12293  ComparisonResult LTFlag = LT, GTFlag = GT;
12294  if (ConstantOnRHS) std::swap(LTFlag, GTFlag);
12295 
12296  if (R & EQ) return StringRef("'std::strong_ordering::equal'");
12297  if (R & LTFlag) return StringRef("'std::strong_ordering::less'");
12298  if (R & GTFlag) return StringRef("'std::strong_ordering::greater'");
12299  return llvm::None;
12300  }
12301 
12302  ComparisonResult TrueFlag, FalseFlag;
12303  if (Op == BO_EQ) {
12304  TrueFlag = EQ;
12305  FalseFlag = NE;
12306  } else if (Op == BO_NE) {
12307  TrueFlag = NE;
12308  FalseFlag = EQ;
12309  } else {
12310  if ((Op == BO_LT || Op == BO_GE) ^ ConstantOnRHS) {
12311  TrueFlag = LT;
12312  FalseFlag = GE;
12313  } else {
12314  TrueFlag = GT;
12315  FalseFlag = LE;
12316  }
12317  if (Op == BO_GE || Op == BO_LE)
12318  std::swap(TrueFlag, FalseFlag);
12319  }
12320  if (R & TrueFlag)
12321  return StringRef("true");
12322  if (R & FalseFlag)
12323  return StringRef("false");
12324  return llvm::None;
12325  }
12326 };
12327 }
12328 
12329 static bool HasEnumType(Expr *E) {
12330  // Strip off implicit integral promotions.
12331  while (ImplicitCastExpr *ICE = dyn_cast<ImplicitCastExpr>(E)) {
12332  if (ICE->getCastKind() != CK_IntegralCast &&
12333  ICE->getCastKind() != CK_NoOp)
12334  break;
12335  E = ICE->getSubExpr();
12336  }
12337 
12338  return E->getType()->isEnumeralType();
12339 }
12340 
12341 static int classifyConstantValue(Expr *Constant) {
12342  // The values of this enumeration are used in the diagnostics
12343  // diag::warn_out_of_range_compare and diag::warn_tautological_bool_compare.
12344  enum ConstantValueKind {
12345  Miscellaneous = 0,
12346  LiteralTrue,
12347  LiteralFalse
12348  };
12349  if (auto *BL = dyn_cast<CXXBoolLiteralExpr>(Constant))
12350  return BL->getValue() ? ConstantValueKind::LiteralTrue
12351  : ConstantValueKind::LiteralFalse;
12352  return ConstantValueKind::Miscellaneous;
12353 }
12354 
12355 static bool CheckTautologicalComparison(Sema &S, BinaryOperator *E,
12356  Expr *Constant, Expr *Other,
12357  const llvm::APSInt &Value,
12358  bool RhsConstant) {
12359  if (S.inTemplateInstantiation())
12360  return false;
12361 
12362  Expr *OriginalOther = Other;
12363 
12364  Constant = Constant->IgnoreParenImpCasts();
12365  Other = Other->IgnoreParenImpCasts();
12366 
12367  // Suppress warnings on tautological comparisons between values of the same
12368  // enumeration type. There are only two ways we could warn on this:
12369  // - If the constant is outside the range of representable values of
12370  // the enumeration. In such a case, we should warn about the cast
12371  // to enumeration type, not about the comparison.
12372  // - If the constant is the maximum / minimum in-range value. For an
12373  // enumeratin type, such comparisons can be meaningful and useful.
12374  if (Constant->getType()->isEnumeralType() &&
12375  S.Context.hasSameUnqualifiedType(Constant->getType(), Other->getType()))
12376  return false;
12377 
12378  IntRange OtherValueRange = GetExprRange(
12379  S.Context, Other, S.isConstantEvaluated(), /*Approximate*/ false);
12380 
12381  QualType OtherT = Other->getType();
12382  if (const auto *AT = OtherT->getAs<AtomicType>())
12383  OtherT = AT->getValueType();
12384  IntRange OtherTypeRange = IntRange::forValueOfType(S.Context, OtherT);
12385 
12386  // Special case for ObjC BOOL on targets where its a typedef for a signed char
12387  // (Namely, macOS). FIXME: IntRange::forValueOfType should do this.
12388  bool IsObjCSignedCharBool = S.getLangOpts().ObjC &&
12389  S.NSAPIObj->isObjCBOOLType(OtherT) &&
12390  OtherT->isSpecificBuiltinType(BuiltinType::SChar);
12391 
12392  // Whether we're treating Other as being a bool because of the form of
12393  // expression despite it having another type (typically 'int' in C).
12394  bool OtherIsBooleanDespiteType =
12395  !OtherT->isBooleanType() && Other->isKnownToHaveBooleanValue();
12396  if (OtherIsBooleanDespiteType || IsObjCSignedCharBool)
12397  OtherTypeRange = OtherValueRange = IntRange::forBoolType();
12398 
12399  // Check if all values in the range of possible values of this expression
12400  // lead to the same comparison outcome.
12401  PromotedRange OtherPromotedValueRange(OtherValueRange, Value.getBitWidth(),
12402  Value.isUnsigned());
12403  auto Cmp = OtherPromotedValueRange.compare(Value);
12404  auto Result = PromotedRange::constantValue(E->getOpcode(), Cmp, RhsConstant);
12405  if (!Result)
12406  return false;
12407 
12408  // Also consider the range determined by the type alone. This allows us to
12409  // classify the warning under the proper diagnostic group.
12410  bool TautologicalTypeCompare = false;
12411  {
12412  PromotedRange OtherPromotedTypeRange(OtherTypeRange, Value.getBitWidth(),
12413  Value.isUnsigned());
12414  auto TypeCmp = OtherPromotedTypeRange.compare(Value);
12415  if (auto TypeResult = PromotedRange::constantValue(E->getOpcode(), TypeCmp,
12416  RhsConstant)) {
12417  TautologicalTypeCompare = true;
12418  Cmp = TypeCmp;
12419  Result = TypeResult;
12420  }
12421  }
12422 
12423  // Don't warn if the non-constant operand actually always evaluates to the
12424  // same value.
12425  if (!TautologicalTypeCompare && OtherValueRange.Width == 0)
12426  return false;
12427 
12428  // Suppress the diagnostic for an in-range comparison if the constant comes
12429  // from a macro or enumerator. We don't want to diagnose
12430  //
12431  // some_long_value <= INT_MAX
12432  //
12433  // when sizeof(int) == sizeof(long).
12434  bool InRange = Cmp & PromotedRange::InRangeFlag;
12435  if (InRange && IsEnumConstOrFromMacro(S, Constant))
12436  return false;
12437 
12438  // A comparison of an unsigned bit-field against 0 is really a type problem,
12439  // even though at the type level the bit-field might promote to 'signed int'.
12440  if (Other->refersToBitField() && InRange && Value == 0 &&
12441  Other->getType()->isUnsignedIntegerOrEnumerationType())
12442  TautologicalTypeCompare = true;
12443 
12444  // If this is a comparison to an enum constant, include that
12445  // constant in the diagnostic.
12446  const EnumConstantDecl *ED = nullptr;
12447  if (const DeclRefExpr *DR = dyn_cast<DeclRefExpr>(Constant))
12448  ED = dyn_cast<EnumConstantDecl>(DR->getDecl());
12449 
12450  // Should be enough for uint128 (39 decimal digits)
12451  SmallString<64> PrettySourceValue;
12452  llvm::raw_svector_ostream OS(PrettySourceValue);
12453  if (ED) {
12454  OS << '\'' << *ED << "' (" << Value << ")";
12455  } else if (auto *BL = dyn_cast<ObjCBoolLiteralExpr>(
12456  Constant->IgnoreParenImpCasts())) {
12457  OS << (BL->getValue() ? "YES" : "NO");
12458  } else {
12459  OS << Value;
12460  }
12461 
12462  if (!TautologicalTypeCompare) {
12463  S.Diag(E->getOperatorLoc(), diag::warn_tautological_compare_value_range)
12464  << RhsConstant << OtherValueRange.Width << OtherValueRange.NonNegative
12465  << E->getOpcodeStr() << OS.str() << *Result
12466  << E->getLHS()->getSourceRange() << E->getRHS()->getSourceRange();
12467  return true;
12468  }
12469 
12470  if (IsObjCSignedCharBool) {
12471  S.DiagRuntimeBehavior(E->getOperatorLoc(), E,
12472  S.PDiag(diag::warn_tautological_compare_objc_bool)
12473  << OS.str() << *Result);
12474  return true;
12475  }
12476 
12477  // FIXME: We use a somewhat different formatting for the in-range cases and
12478  // cases involving boolean values for historical reasons. We should pick a
12479  // consistent way of presenting these diagnostics.
12480  if (!InRange || Other->isKnownToHaveBooleanValue()) {
12481 
12482  S.DiagRuntimeBehavior(
12483  E->getOperatorLoc(), E,
12484  S.PDiag(!InRange ? diag::warn_out_of_range_compare
12485  : diag::warn_tautological_bool_compare)
12486  << OS.str() << classifyConstantValue(Constant) << OtherT
12487  << OtherIsBooleanDespiteType << *Result
12488  << E->getLHS()->getSourceRange() << E->getRHS()->getSourceRange());
12489  } else {
12490  bool IsCharTy = OtherT.withoutLocalFastQualifiers() == S.Context.CharTy;
12491  unsigned Diag =
12492  (isKnownToHaveUnsignedValue(OriginalOther) && Value == 0)
12493  ? (HasEnumType(OriginalOther)
12494  ? diag::warn_unsigned_enum_always_true_comparison
12495  : IsCharTy ? diag::warn_unsigned_char_always_true_comparison
12496  : diag::warn_unsigned_always_true_comparison)
12497  : diag::warn_tautological_constant_compare;
12498 
12499  S.Diag(E->getOperatorLoc(), Diag)
12500  << RhsConstant << OtherT << E->getOpcodeStr() << OS.str() << *Result
12501  << E->getLHS()->getSourceRange() << E->getRHS()->getSourceRange();
12502  }
12503 
12504  return true;
12505 }
12506 
12507 /// Analyze the operands of the given comparison. Implements the
12508 /// fallback case from AnalyzeComparison.
12509 static void AnalyzeImpConvsInComparison(Sema &S, BinaryOperator *E) {
12510  AnalyzeImplicitConversions(S, E->getLHS(), E->getOperatorLoc());
12511  AnalyzeImplicitConversions(S, E->getRHS(), E->getOperatorLoc());
12512 }
12513 
12514 /// Implements -Wsign-compare.
12515 ///
12516 /// \param E the binary operator to check for warnings
12517 static void AnalyzeComparison(Sema &S, BinaryOperator *E) {
12518  // The type the comparison is being performed in.
12519  QualType T = E->getLHS()->getType();
12520 
12521  // Only analyze comparison operators where both sides have been converted to
12522  // the same type.
12523  if (!S.Context.hasSameUnqualifiedType(T, E->getRHS()->getType()))
12524  return AnalyzeImpConvsInComparison(S, E);
12525 
12526  // Don't analyze value-dependent comparisons directly.
12527  if (E->isValueDependent())
12528  return AnalyzeImpConvsInComparison(S, E);
12529 
12530  Expr *LHS = E->getLHS();
12531  Expr *RHS = E->getRHS();
12532 
12533  if (T->isIntegralType(S.Context)) {
12534  Optional<llvm::APSInt> RHSValue = RHS->getIntegerConstantExpr(S.Context);
12535  Optional<llvm::APSInt> LHSValue = LHS->getIntegerConstantExpr(S.Context);
12536 
12537  // We don't care about expressions whose result is a constant.
12538  if (RHSValue && LHSValue)
12539  return AnalyzeImpConvsInComparison(S, E);
12540 
12541  // We only care about expressions where just one side is literal
12542  if ((bool)RHSValue ^ (bool)LHSValue) {
12543  // Is the constant on the RHS or LHS?
12544  const bool RhsConstant = (bool)RHSValue;
12545  Expr *Const = RhsConstant ? RHS : LHS;
12546  Expr *Other = RhsConstant ? LHS : RHS;
12547  const llvm::APSInt &Value = RhsConstant ? *RHSValue : *LHSValue;
12548 
12549  // Check whether an integer constant comparison results in a value
12550  // of 'true' or 'false'.
12551  if (CheckTautologicalComparison(S, E, Const, Other, Value, RhsConstant))
12552  return AnalyzeImpConvsInComparison(S, E);
12553  }
12554  }
12555 
12556  if (!T->hasUnsignedIntegerRepresentation()) {
12557  // We don't do anything special if this isn't an unsigned integral
12558  // comparison: we're only interested in integral comparisons, and
12559  // signed comparisons only happen in cases we don't care to warn about.
12560  return AnalyzeImpConvsInComparison(S, E);
12561  }
12562 
12563  LHS = LHS->IgnoreParenImpCasts();
12564  RHS = RHS->IgnoreParenImpCasts();
12565 
12566  if (!S.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus) {
12567  // Avoid warning about comparison of integers with different signs when
12568  // RHS/LHS has a `typeof(E)` type whose sign is different from the sign of
12569  // the type of `E`.
12570  if (const auto *TET = dyn_cast<TypeOfExprType>(LHS->getType()))
12571  LHS = TET->getUnderlyingExpr()->IgnoreParenImpCasts();
12572  if (const auto *TET = dyn_cast<TypeOfExprType>(RHS->getType()))
12573  RHS = TET->getUnderlyingExpr()->IgnoreParenImpCasts();
12574  }
12575 
12576  // Check to see if one of the (unmodified) operands is of different
12577  // signedness.
12578  Expr *signedOperand, *unsignedOperand;
12579  if (LHS->getType()->hasSignedIntegerRepresentation()) {
12580  assert(!RHS->getType()->hasSignedIntegerRepresentation() &&
12581  "unsigned comparison between two signed integer expressions?");
12582  signedOperand = LHS;
12583  unsignedOperand = RHS;
12584  } else if (RHS->getType()->hasSignedIntegerRepresentation()) {
12585  signedOperand = RHS;
12586  unsignedOperand = LHS;
12587  } else {
12588  return AnalyzeImpConvsInComparison(S, E);
12589  }
12590 
12591  // Otherwise, calculate the effective range of the signed operand.
12592  IntRange signedRange = GetExprRange(
12593  S.Context, signedOperand, S.isConstantEvaluated(), /*Approximate*/ true);
12594 
12595  // Go ahead and analyze implicit conversions in the operands. Note
12596  // that we skip the implicit conversions on both sides.
12597  AnalyzeImplicitConversions(S, LHS, E->getOperatorLoc());
12598  AnalyzeImplicitConversions(S, RHS, E->getOperatorLoc());
12599 
12600  // If the signed range is non-negative, -Wsign-compare won't fire.
12601  if (signedRange.NonNegative)
12602  return;
12603 
12604  // For (in)equality comparisons, if the unsigned operand is a
12605  // constant which cannot collide with a overflowed signed operand,
12606  // then reinterpreting the signed operand as unsigned will not
12607  // change the result of the comparison.
12608  if (E->isEqualityOp()) {
12609  unsigned comparisonWidth = S.Context.getIntWidth(T);
12610  IntRange unsignedRange =
12611  GetExprRange(S.Context, unsignedOperand, S.isConstantEvaluated(),
12612  /*Approximate*/ true);
12613 
12614  // We should never be unable to prove that the unsigned operand is
12615  // non-negative.
12616  assert(unsignedRange.NonNegative && "unsigned range includes negative?");
12617 
12618  if (unsignedRange.Width < comparisonWidth)
12619  return;
12620  }
12621 
12622  S.DiagRuntimeBehavior(E->getOperatorLoc(), E,
12623  S.PDiag(diag::warn_mixed_sign_comparison)
12624  << LHS->getType() << RHS->getType()
12625  << LHS->getSourceRange() << RHS->getSourceRange());
12626 }
12627 
12628 /// Analyzes an attempt to assign the given value to a bitfield.
12629 ///
12630 /// Returns true if there was something fishy about the attempt.
12631 static bool AnalyzeBitFieldAssignment(Sema &S, FieldDecl *Bitfield, Expr *Init,
12632  SourceLocation InitLoc) {
12633  assert(Bitfield->isBitField());
12634  if (Bitfield->isInvalidDecl())
12635  return false;
12636 
12637  // White-list bool bitfields.
12638  QualType BitfieldType = Bitfield->getType();
12639  if (BitfieldType->isBooleanType())
12640  return false;
12641 
12642  if (BitfieldType->isEnumeralType()) {
12643  EnumDecl *BitfieldEnumDecl = BitfieldType->castAs<EnumType>()->getDecl();
12644  // If the underlying enum type was not explicitly specified as an unsigned
12645  // type and the enum contain only positive values, MSVC++ will cause an
12646  // inconsistency by storing this as a signed type.
12647  if (S.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus11 &&
12648  !BitfieldEnumDecl->getIntegerTypeSourceInfo() &&
12649  BitfieldEnumDecl->getNumPositiveBits() > 0 &&
12650  BitfieldEnumDecl->getNumNegativeBits() == 0) {
12651  S.Diag(InitLoc, diag::warn_no_underlying_type_specified_for_enum_bitfield)
12652  << BitfieldEnumDecl;
12653  }
12654  }
12655 
12656  if (Bitfield->getType()->isBooleanType())
12657  return false;
12658 
12659  // Ignore value- or type-dependent expressions.
12660  if (Bitfield->getBitWidth()->isValueDependent() ||
12661  Bitfield->getBitWidth()->isTypeDependent() ||
12662  Init->isValueDependent() ||
12663  Init->isTypeDependent())
12664  return false;
12665 
12666  Expr *OriginalInit = Init->IgnoreParenImpCasts();
12667  unsigned FieldWidth = Bitfield->getBitWidthValue(S.Context);
12668 
12669  Expr::EvalResult Result;
12670  if (!OriginalInit->EvaluateAsInt(Result, S.Context,
12671  Expr::SE_AllowSideEffects)) {
12672  // The RHS is not constant. If the RHS has an enum type, make sure the
12673  // bitfield is wide enough to hold all the values of the enum without
12674  // truncation.
12675  if (const auto *EnumTy = OriginalInit->getType()->getAs<EnumType>()) {
12676  EnumDecl *ED = EnumTy->getDecl();
12677  bool SignedBitfield = BitfieldType->isSignedIntegerType();
12678 
12679  // Enum types are implicitly signed on Windows, so check if there are any
12680  // negative enumerators to see if the enum was intended to be signed or
12681  // not.
12682  bool SignedEnum = ED->getNumNegativeBits() > 0;
12683 
12684  // Check for surprising sign changes when assigning enum values to a
12685  // bitfield of different signedness. If the bitfield is signed and we
12686  // have exactly the right number of bits to store this unsigned enum,
12687  // suggest changing the enum to an unsigned type. This typically happens
12688  // on Windows where unfixed enums always use an underlying type of 'int'.
12689  unsigned DiagID = 0;
12690  if (SignedEnum && !SignedBitfield) {
12691  DiagID = diag::warn_unsigned_bitfield_assigned_signed_enum;
12692  } else if (SignedBitfield && !SignedEnum &&
12693  ED->getNumPositiveBits() == FieldWidth) {
12694  DiagID = diag::warn_signed_bitfield_enum_conversion;
12695  }
12696 
12697  if (DiagID) {
12698  S.Diag(InitLoc, DiagID) << Bitfield << ED;
12699  TypeSourceInfo *TSI = Bitfield->getTypeSourceInfo();
12700  SourceRange TypeRange =
12701  TSI ? TSI->getTypeLoc().getSourceRange() : SourceRange();
12702  S.Diag(Bitfield->getTypeSpecStartLoc(), diag::note_change_bitfield_sign)
12703  << SignedEnum << TypeRange;
12704  }
12705 
12706  // Compute the required bitwidth. If the enum has negative values, we need
12707  // one more bit than the normal number of positive bits to represent the
12708  // sign bit.
12709  unsigned BitsNeeded = SignedEnum ? std::max(ED->getNumPositiveBits() + 1,
12710  ED->getNumNegativeBits())
12711  : ED->getNumPositiveBits();
12712 
12713  // Check the bitwidth.
12714  if (BitsNeeded > FieldWidth) {
12715  Expr *WidthExpr = Bitfield->getBitWidth();
12716  S.Diag(InitLoc, diag::warn_bitfield_too_small_for_enum)
12717  << Bitfield << ED;
12718  S.Diag(WidthExpr->getExprLoc(), diag::note_widen_bitfield)
12719  << BitsNeeded << ED << WidthExpr->getSourceRange();
12720  }
12721  }
12722 
12723  return false;
12724  }
12725 
12726  llvm::APSInt Value = Result.Val.getInt();
12727 
12728  unsigned OriginalWidth = Value.getBitWidth();
12729 
12730  if (!Value.isSigned() || Value.isNegative())
12731  if (UnaryOperator *UO = dyn_cast<UnaryOperator>(OriginalInit))
12732  if (UO->getOpcode() == UO_Minus || UO->getOpcode() == UO_Not)
12733  OriginalWidth = Value.getMinSignedBits();
12734 
12735  if (OriginalWidth <= FieldWidth)
12736  return false;
12737 
12738  // Compute the value which the bitfield will contain.
12739  llvm::APSInt TruncatedValue = Value.trunc(FieldWidth);
12740  TruncatedValue.setIsSigned(BitfieldType->isSignedIntegerType());
12741 
12742  // Check whether the stored value is equal to the original value.
12743  TruncatedValue = TruncatedValue.extend(OriginalWidth);
12744  if (llvm::APSInt::isSameValue(Value, TruncatedValue))
12745  return false;
12746 
12747  // Special-case bitfields of width 1: booleans are naturally 0/1, and
12748  // therefore don't strictly fit into a signed bitfield of width 1.
12749  if (FieldWidth == 1 && Value == 1)
12750  return false;
12751 
12752  std::string PrettyValue = toString(Value, 10);
12753  std::string PrettyTrunc = toString(TruncatedValue, 10);
12754 
12755  S.Diag(InitLoc, diag::warn_impcast_bitfield_precision_constant)
12756  << PrettyValue << PrettyTrunc << OriginalInit->getType()
12757  << Init->getSourceRange();
12758 
12759  return true;
12760 }
12761 
12762 /// Analyze the given simple or compound assignment for warning-worthy
12763 /// operations.
12764 static void AnalyzeAssignment(Sema &S, BinaryOperator *E) {
12765  // Just recurse on the LHS.
12766  AnalyzeImplicitConversions(S, E->getLHS(), E->getOperatorLoc());
12767 
12768  // We want to recurse on the RHS as normal unless we're assigning to
12769  // a bitfield.
12770  if (FieldDecl *Bitfield = E->getLHS()->getSourceBitField()) {
12771  if (AnalyzeBitFieldAssignment(S, Bitfield, E->getRHS(),
12772  E->getOperatorLoc())) {
12773  // Recurse, ignoring any implicit conversions on the RHS.
12774  return AnalyzeImplicitConversions(S, E->getRHS()->IgnoreParenImpCasts(),
12775  E->getOperatorLoc());
12776  }
12777  }
12778 
12779  AnalyzeImplicitConversions(S, E->getRHS(), E->getOperatorLoc());
12780 
12781  // Diagnose implicitly sequentially-consistent atomic assignment.
12782  if (E->getLHS()->getType()->isAtomicType())
12783  S.Diag(E->getRHS()->getBeginLoc(), diag::warn_atomic_implicit_seq_cst);
12784 }
12785 
12786 /// Diagnose an implicit cast; purely a helper for CheckImplicitConversion.
12787 static void DiagnoseImpCast(Sema &S, Expr *E, QualType SourceType, QualType T,
12788  SourceLocation CContext, unsigned diag,
12789  bool pruneControlFlow = false) {
12790  if (pruneControlFlow) {
12791  S.DiagRuntimeBehavior(E->getExprLoc(), E,
12792  S.PDiag(diag)
12793  << SourceType << T << E->getSourceRange()
12794  << SourceRange(CContext));
12795  return;
12796  }
12797  S.Diag(E->getExprLoc(), diag)
12798  << SourceType << T << E->getSourceRange() << SourceRange(CContext);
12799 }
12800 
12801 /// Diagnose an implicit cast; purely a helper for CheckImplicitConversion.
12802 static void DiagnoseImpCast(Sema &S, Expr *E, QualType T,
12803  SourceLocation CContext,
12804  unsigned diag, bool pruneControlFlow = false) {
12805  DiagnoseImpCast(S, E, E->getType(), T, CContext, diag, pruneControlFlow);
12806 }
12807 
12808 static bool isObjCSignedCharBool(Sema &S, QualType Ty) {
12809  return Ty->isSpecificBuiltinType(BuiltinType::SChar) &&
12810  S.getLangOpts().ObjC && S.NSAPIObj->isObjCBOOLType(Ty);
12811 }
12812 
12813 static void adornObjCBoolConversionDiagWithTernaryFixit(
12814  Sema &S, Expr *SourceExpr, const Sema::SemaDiagnosticBuilder &Builder) {
12815  Expr *Ignored = SourceExpr->IgnoreImplicit();
12816  if (const auto *OVE = dyn_cast<OpaqueValueExpr>(Ignored))
12817  Ignored = OVE->getSourceExpr();
12818  bool NeedsParens = isa<AbstractConditionalOperator>(Ignored) ||
12819  isa<BinaryOperator>(Ignored) ||
12820  isa<CXXOperatorCallExpr>(Ignored);
12821  SourceLocation EndLoc = S.getLocForEndOfToken(SourceExpr->getEndLoc());
12822  if (NeedsParens)
12823  Builder << FixItHint::CreateInsertion(SourceExpr->getBeginLoc(), "(")
12824  << FixItHint::CreateInsertion(EndLoc, ")");
12825  Builder << FixItHint::CreateInsertion(EndLoc, " ? YES : NO");
12826 }
12827 
12828 /// Diagnose an implicit cast from a floating point value to an integer value.
12829 static void DiagnoseFloatingImpCast(Sema &S, Expr *E, QualType T,
12830  SourceLocation CContext) {
12831  const bool IsBool = T->isSpecificBuiltinType(BuiltinType::Bool);
12832  const bool PruneWarnings = S.inTemplateInstantiation();
12833 
12834  Expr *InnerE = E->IgnoreParenImpCasts();
12835  // We also want to warn on, e.g., "int i = -1.234"
12836  if (UnaryOperator *UOp = dyn_cast<UnaryOperator>(InnerE))
12837  if (UOp->getOpcode() == UO_Minus || UOp->getOpcode() == UO_Plus)
12838  InnerE = UOp->getSubExpr()->IgnoreParenImpCasts();
12839 
12840  const bool IsLiteral =
12841  isa<FloatingLiteral>(E) || isa<FloatingLiteral>(InnerE);
12842 
12843  llvm::APFloat Value(0.0);
12844  bool IsConstant =
12845  E->EvaluateAsFloat(Value, S.Context, Expr::SE_AllowSideEffects);
12846  if (!IsConstant) {
12847  if (isObjCSignedCharBool(S, T)) {
12848  return adornObjCBoolConversionDiagWithTernaryFixit(
12849  S, E,
12850  S.Diag(CContext, diag::warn_impcast_float_to_objc_signed_char_bool)
12851  << E->getType());
12852  }
12853 
12854  return DiagnoseImpCast(S, E, T, CContext,
12855  diag::warn_impcast_float_integer, PruneWarnings);
12856  }
12857 
12858  bool isExact = false;
12859 
12860  llvm::APSInt IntegerValue(S.Context.getIntWidth(T),
12861  T->hasUnsignedIntegerRepresentation());
12862  llvm::APFloat::opStatus Result = Value.convertToInteger(
12863  IntegerValue, llvm::APFloat::rmTowardZero, &isExact);
12864 
12865  // FIXME: Force the precision of the source value down so we don't print
12866  // digits which are usually useless (we don't really care here if we
12867  // truncate a digit by accident in edge cases). Ideally, APFloat::toString
12868  // would automatically print the shortest representation, but it's a bit
12869  // tricky to implement.
12870  SmallString<16> PrettySourceValue;
12871  unsigned precision = llvm::APFloat::semanticsPrecision(Value.getSemantics());
12872  precision = (precision * 59 + 195) / 196;
12873  Value.toString(PrettySourceValue, precision);
12874 
12875  if (isObjCSignedCharBool(S, T) && IntegerValue != 0 && IntegerValue != 1) {
12876  return adornObjCBoolConversionDiagWithTernaryFixit(
12877  S, E,
12878  S.Diag(CContext, diag::warn_impcast_constant_value_to_objc_bool)
12879  << PrettySourceValue);
12880  }
12881 
12882  if (Result == llvm::APFloat::opOK && isExact) {
12883  if (IsLiteral) return;
12884  return DiagnoseImpCast(S, E, T, CContext, diag::warn_impcast_float_integer,
12885  PruneWarnings);
12886  }
12887 
12888  // Conversion of a floating-point value to a non-bool integer where the
12889  // integral part cannot be represented by the integer type is undefined.
12890  if (!IsBool && Result == llvm::APFloat::opInvalidOp)
12891  return DiagnoseImpCast(
12892  S, E, T, CContext,
12893  IsLiteral ? diag::warn_impcast_literal_float_to_integer_out_of_range
12894  : diag::warn_impcast_float_to_integer_out_of_range,
12895  PruneWarnings);
12896 
12897  unsigned DiagID = 0;
12898  if (IsLiteral) {
12899  // Warn on floating point literal to integer.
12900  DiagID = diag::warn_impcast_literal_float_to_integer;
12901  } else if (IntegerValue == 0) {
12902  if (Value.isZero()) { // Skip -0.0 to 0 conversion.
12903  return DiagnoseImpCast(S, E, T, CContext,
12904  diag::warn_impcast_float_integer, PruneWarnings);
12905  }
12906  // Warn on non-zero to zero conversion.
12907  DiagID = diag::warn_impcast_float_to_integer_zero;
12908  } else {
12909  if (IntegerValue.isUnsigned()) {
12910  if (!IntegerValue.isMaxValue()) {
12911  return DiagnoseImpCast(S, E, T, CContext,
12912  diag::warn_impcast_float_integer, PruneWarnings);
12913  }
12914  } else { // IntegerValue.isSigned()
12915  if (!IntegerValue.isMaxSignedValue() &&
12916  !IntegerValue.isMinSignedValue()) {
12917  return DiagnoseImpCast(S, E, T, CContext,
12918  diag::warn_impcast_float_integer, PruneWarnings);
12919  }
12920  }
12921  // Warn on evaluatable floating point expression to integer conversion.
12922  DiagID = diag::warn_impcast_float_to_integer;
12923  }
12924 
12925  SmallString<16> PrettyTargetValue;
12926  if (IsBool)
12927  PrettyTargetValue = Value.isZero() ? "false" : "true";
12928  else
12929  IntegerValue.toString(PrettyTargetValue);
12930 
12931  if (PruneWarnings) {
12932  S.DiagRuntimeBehavior(E->getExprLoc(), E,
12933  S.PDiag(DiagID)
12934  << E->getType() << T.getUnqualifiedType()
12935  << PrettySourceValue << PrettyTargetValue
12936  << E->getSourceRange() << SourceRange(CContext));
12937  } else {
12938  S.Diag(E->getExprLoc(), DiagID)
12939  << E->getType() << T.getUnqualifiedType() << PrettySourceValue
12940  << PrettyTargetValue << E->getSourceRange() << SourceRange(CContext);
12941  }
12942 }
12943 
12944 /// Analyze the given compound assignment for the possible losing of
12945 /// floating-point precision.
12946 static void AnalyzeCompoundAssignment(Sema &S, BinaryOperator *E) {
12947  assert(isa<CompoundAssignOperator>(E) &&
12948  "Must be compound assignment operation");
12949  // Recurse on the LHS and RHS in here
12950  AnalyzeImplicitConversions(S, E->getLHS(), E->getOperatorLoc());
12951  AnalyzeImplicitConversions(S, E->getRHS(), E->getOperatorLoc());
12952 
12953  if (E->getLHS()->getType()->isAtomicType())
12954  S.Diag(E->getOperatorLoc(), diag::warn_atomic_implicit_seq_cst);
12955 
12956  // Now check the outermost expression
12957  const auto *ResultBT = E->getLHS()->getType()->getAs<BuiltinType>();
12958  const auto *RBT = cast<CompoundAssignOperator>(E)
12959  ->getComputationResultType()
12960  ->getAs<BuiltinType>();
12961 
12962  // The below checks assume source is floating point.
12963  if (!ResultBT || !RBT || !RBT->isFloatingPoint()) return;
12964 
12965  // If source is floating point but target is an integer.
12966  if (ResultBT->isInteger())
12967  return DiagnoseImpCast(S, E, E->getRHS()->getType(), E->getLHS()->getType(),
12968  E->getExprLoc(), diag::warn_impcast_float_integer);
12969 
12970  if (!ResultBT->isFloatingPoint())
12971  return;
12972 
12973  // If both source and target are floating points, warn about losing precision.
12974  int Order = S.getASTContext().getFloatingTypeSemanticOrder(
12975  QualType(ResultBT, 0), QualType(RBT, 0));
12976  if (Order < 0 && !S.SourceMgr.isInSystemMacro(E->getOperatorLoc()))
12977  // warn about dropping FP rank.
12978  DiagnoseImpCast(S, E->getRHS(), E->getLHS()->getType(), E->getOperatorLoc(),
12979  diag::warn_impcast_float_result_precision);
12980 }
12981 
12982 static std::string PrettyPrintInRange(const llvm::APSInt &Value,
12983  IntRange Range) {
12984  if (!Range.Width) return "0";
12985 
12986  llvm::APSInt ValueInRange = Value;
12987  ValueInRange.setIsSigned(!Range.NonNegative);
12988  ValueInRange = ValueInRange.trunc(Range.Width);
12989  return toString(ValueInRange, 10);
12990 }
12991 
12992 static bool IsImplicitBoolFloatConversion(Sema &S, Expr *Ex, bool ToBool) {
12993  if (!isa<ImplicitCastExpr>(Ex))
12994  return false;
12995 
12996  Expr *InnerE = Ex->IgnoreParenImpCasts();
12997  const Type *Target = S.Context.getCanonicalType(Ex->getType()).getTypePtr();
12998  const Type *Source =
12999  S.Context.getCanonicalType(InnerE->getType()).getTypePtr();
13000  if (Target->isDependentType())
13001  return false;
13002 
13003  const BuiltinType *FloatCandidateBT =
13004  dyn_cast<BuiltinType>(ToBool ? Source : Target);
13005  const Type *BoolCandidateType = ToBool ? Target : Source;
13006 
13007  return (BoolCandidateType->isSpecificBuiltinType(BuiltinType::Bool) &&
13008  FloatCandidateBT && (FloatCandidateBT->isFloatingPoint()));
13009 }
13010 
13011 static void CheckImplicitArgumentConversions(Sema &S, CallExpr *TheCall,
13012  SourceLocation CC) {
13013  unsigned NumArgs = TheCall->getNumArgs();
13014  for (unsigned i = 0; i < NumArgs; ++i) {
13015  Expr *CurrA = TheCall->getArg(i);
13016  if (!IsImplicitBoolFloatConversion(S, CurrA, true))
13017  continue;
13018 
13019  bool IsSwapped = ((i > 0) &&
13020  IsImplicitBoolFloatConversion(S, TheCall->getArg(i - 1), false));
13021  IsSwapped |= ((i < (NumArgs - 1)) &&
13022  IsImplicitBoolFloatConversion(S, TheCall->getArg(i + 1), false));
13023  if (IsSwapped) {
13024  // Warn on this floating-point to bool conversion.
13025  DiagnoseImpCast(S, CurrA->IgnoreParenImpCasts(),
13026  CurrA->getType(), CC,
13027  diag::warn_impcast_floating_point_to_bool);
13028  }
13029  }
13030 }
13031 
13032 static void DiagnoseNullConversion(Sema &S, Expr *E, QualType T,
13033  SourceLocation CC) {
13034  if (S.Diags.isIgnored(diag::warn_impcast_null_pointer_to_integer,
13035  E->getExprLoc()))
13036  return;
13037 
13038  // Don't warn on functions which have return type nullptr_t.
13039  if (isa<CallExpr>(E))
13040  return;
13041 
13042  // Check for NULL (GNUNull) or nullptr (CXX11_nullptr).
13043  const Expr::NullPointerConstantKind NullKind =
13044  E->isNullPointerConstant(S.Context, Expr::NPC_ValueDependentIsNotNull);
13045  if (NullKind != Expr::NPCK_GNUNull && NullKind != Expr::NPCK_CXX11_nullptr)
13046  return;
13047 
13048  // Return if target type is a safe conversion.
13049  if (T->isAnyPointerType() || T->isBlockPointerType() ||
13050  T->isMemberPointerType() || !T->isScalarType() || T->isNullPtrType())
13051  return;
13052 
13053  SourceLocation Loc = E->getSourceRange().getBegin();
13054 
13055  // Venture through the macro stacks to get to the source of macro arguments.
13056  // The new location is a better location than the complete location that was
13057  // passed in.
13058  Loc = S.SourceMgr.getTopMacroCallerLoc(Loc);
13059  CC = S.SourceMgr.getTopMacroCallerLoc(CC);
13060 
13061  // __null is usually wrapped in a macro. Go up a macro if that is the case.
13062  if (NullKind == Expr::NPCK_GNUNull && Loc.isMacroID()) {
13063  StringRef MacroName = Lexer::getImmediateMacroNameForDiagnostics(
13064  Loc, S.SourceMgr, S.getLangOpts());
13065  if (MacroName == "NULL")
13066  Loc = S.SourceMgr.getImmediateExpansionRange(Loc).getBegin();
13067  }
13068 
13069  // Only warn if the null and context location are in the same macro expansion.
13070  if (S.SourceMgr.getFileID(Loc) != S.SourceMgr.getFileID(CC))
13071  return;
13072 
13073  S.Diag(Loc, diag::warn_impcast_null_pointer_to_integer)
13074  << (NullKind == Expr::NPCK_CXX11_nullptr) << T << SourceRange(CC)
13075  << FixItHint::CreateReplacement(Loc,
13076  S.getFixItZeroLiteralForType(T, Loc));
13077 }
13078 
13079 static void checkObjCArrayLiteral(Sema &S, QualType TargetType,
13080  ObjCArrayLiteral *ArrayLiteral);
13081 
13082 static void
13083 checkObjCDictionaryLiteral(Sema &S, QualType TargetType,
13084  ObjCDictionaryLiteral *DictionaryLiteral);
13085 
13086 /// Check a single element within a collection literal against the
13087 /// target element type.
13088 static void checkObjCCollectionLiteralElement(Sema &S,
13089  QualType TargetElementType,
13090  Expr *Element,
13091  unsigned ElementKind) {
13092  // Skip a bitcast to 'id' or qualified 'id'.
13093  if (auto ICE = dyn_cast<ImplicitCastExpr>(Element)) {
13094  if (ICE->getCastKind() == CK_BitCast &&
13095  ICE->getSubExpr()->getType()->getAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>())
13096  Element = ICE->getSubExpr();
13097  }
13098 
13099  QualType ElementType = Element->getType();
13100  ExprResult ElementResult(Element);
13101  if (ElementType->getAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>() &&
13102  S.CheckSingleAssignmentConstraints(TargetElementType,
13103  ElementResult,
13104  false, false)
13105  != Sema::Compatible) {
13106  S.Diag(Element->getBeginLoc(), diag::warn_objc_collection_literal_element)
13107  << ElementType << ElementKind << TargetElementType
13108  << Element->getSourceRange();
13109  }
13110 
13111  if (auto ArrayLiteral = dyn_cast<ObjCArrayLiteral>(Element))
13112  checkObjCArrayLiteral(S, TargetElementType, ArrayLiteral);
13113  else if (auto DictionaryLiteral = dyn_cast<ObjCDictionaryLiteral>(Element))
13114  checkObjCDictionaryLiteral(S, TargetElementType, DictionaryLiteral);
13115 }
13116 
13117 /// Check an Objective-C array literal being converted to the given
13118 /// target type.
13119 static void checkObjCArrayLiteral(Sema &S, QualType TargetType,
13120  ObjCArrayLiteral *ArrayLiteral) {
13121  if (!S.NSArrayDecl)
13122  return;
13123 
13124  const auto *TargetObjCPtr = TargetType->getAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>();
13125  if (!TargetObjCPtr)
13126  return;
13127 
13128  if (TargetObjCPtr->isUnspecialized() ||
13129  TargetObjCPtr->getInterfaceDecl()->getCanonicalDecl()
13130  != S.NSArrayDecl->getCanonicalDecl())
13131  return;
13132 
13133  auto TypeArgs = TargetObjCPtr->getTypeArgs();
13134  if (TypeArgs.size() != 1)
13135  return;
13136 
13137  QualType TargetElementType = TypeArgs[0];
13138  for (unsigned I = 0, N = ArrayLiteral->getNumElements(); I != N; ++I) {
13139  checkObjCCollectionLiteralElement(S, TargetElementType,
13140  ArrayLiteral->getElement(I),
13141  0);
13142  }
13143 }
13144 
13145 /// Check an Objective-C dictionary literal being converted to the given
13146 /// target type.
13147 static void
13148 checkObjCDictionaryLiteral(Sema &S, QualType TargetType,
13149  ObjCDictionaryLiteral *DictionaryLiteral) {
13150  if (!S.NSDictionaryDecl)
13151  return;
13152 
13153  const auto *TargetObjCPtr = TargetType->getAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>();
13154  if (!TargetObjCPtr)
13155  return;
13156 
13157  if (TargetObjCPtr->isUnspecialized() ||
13158  TargetObjCPtr->getInterfaceDecl()->getCanonicalDecl()
13159  != S.NSDictionaryDecl->getCanonicalDecl())
13160  return;
13161 
13162  auto TypeArgs = TargetObjCPtr->getTypeArgs();
13163  if (TypeArgs.size() != 2)
13164  return;
13165 
13166  QualType TargetKeyType = TypeArgs[0];
13167  QualType TargetObjectType = TypeArgs[1];
13168  for (unsigned I = 0, N = DictionaryLiteral->getNumElements(); I != N; ++I) {
13169  auto Element = DictionaryLiteral->getKeyValueElement(I);
13170  checkObjCCollectionLiteralElement(S, TargetKeyType, Element.Key, 1);
13171  checkObjCCollectionLiteralElement(S, TargetObjectType, Element.Value, 2);
13172  }
13173 }
13174 
13175 // Helper function to filter out cases for constant width constant conversion.
13176 // Don't warn on char array initialization or for non-decimal values.
13177 static bool isSameWidthConstantConversion(Sema &S, Expr *E, QualType T,
13178  SourceLocation CC) {
13179  // If initializing from a constant, and the constant starts with '0',
13180  // then it is a binary, octal, or hexadecimal. Allow these constants
13181  // to fill all the bits, even if there is a sign change.
13182  if (auto *IntLit = dyn_cast<IntegerLiteral>(E->IgnoreParenImpCasts())) {
13183  const char FirstLiteralCharacter =
13184  S.getSourceManager().getCharacterData(IntLit->getBeginLoc())[0];
13185  if (FirstLiteralCharacter == '0')
13186  return false;
13187  }
13188 
13189  // If the CC location points to a '{', and the type is char, then assume
13190  // assume it is an array initialization.
13191  if (CC.isValid() && T->isCharType()) {
13192  const char FirstContextCharacter =
13193  S.getSourceManager().getCharacterData(CC)[0];
13194  if (FirstContextCharacter == '{')
13195  return false;
13196  }
13197 
13198  return true;
13199 }
13200 
13201 static const IntegerLiteral *getIntegerLiteral(Expr *E) {
13202  const auto *IL = dyn_cast<IntegerLiteral>(E);
13203  if (!IL) {
13204  if (auto *UO = dyn_cast<UnaryOperator>(E)) {
13205  if (UO->getOpcode() == UO_Minus)
13206  return dyn_cast<IntegerLiteral>(UO->getSubExpr());
13207  }
13208  }
13209 
13210  return IL;
13211 }
13212 
13213 static void DiagnoseIntInBoolContext(Sema &S, Expr *E) {
13214  E = E->IgnoreParenImpCasts();
13215  SourceLocation ExprLoc = E->getExprLoc();
13216 
13217  if (const auto *BO = dyn_cast<BinaryOperator>(E)) {
13218  BinaryOperator::Opcode Opc = BO->getOpcode();
13219  Expr::EvalResult Result;
13220  // Do not diagnose unsigned shifts.
13221  if (Opc == BO_Shl) {
13222  const auto *LHS = getIntegerLiteral(BO->getLHS());
13223  const auto *RHS = getIntegerLiteral(BO->getRHS());
13224  if (LHS && LHS->getValue() == 0)
13225  S.Diag(ExprLoc, diag::warn_left_shift_always) << 0;
13226  else if (!E->isValueDependent() && LHS && RHS &&
13227  RHS->getValue().isNonNegative() &&
13228  E->EvaluateAsInt(Result, S.Context, Expr::SE_AllowSideEffects))
13229  S.Diag(ExprLoc, diag::warn_left_shift_always)
13230  << (Result.Val.getInt() != 0);
13231  else if (E->getType()->isSignedIntegerType())
13232  S.Diag(ExprLoc, diag::warn_left_shift_in_bool_context) << E;
13233  }
13234  }
13235 
13236  if (const auto *CO = dyn_cast<ConditionalOperator>(E)) {
13237  const auto *LHS = getIntegerLiteral(CO->getTrueExpr());
13238  const auto *RHS = getIntegerLiteral(CO->getFalseExpr());
13239  if (!LHS || !RHS)
13240  return;
13241  if ((LHS->getValue() == 0 || LHS->getValue() == 1) &&
13242  (RHS->getValue() == 0 || RHS->getValue() == 1))
13243  // Do not diagnose common idioms.
13244  return;
13245  if (LHS->getValue() != 0 && RHS->getValue() != 0)
13246  S.Diag(ExprLoc, diag::warn_integer_constants_in_conditional_always_true);
13247  }
13248 }
13249 
13250 static void CheckImplicitConversion(Sema &S, Expr *E, QualType T,
13251  SourceLocation CC,
13252  bool *ICContext = nullptr,
13253  bool IsListInit = false) {
13254  if (E->isTypeDependent() || E->isValueDependent()) return;
13255 
13256  const Type *Source = S.Context.getCanonicalType(E->getType()).getTypePtr();
13257  const Type *Target = S.Context.getCanonicalType(T).getTypePtr();
13258  if (Source == Target) return;
13259  if (Target->isDependentType()) return;
13260 
13261  // If the conversion context location is invalid don't complain. We also
13262  // don't want to emit a warning if the issue occurs from the expansion of
13263  // a system macro. The problem is that 'getSpellingLoc()' is slow, so we
13264  // delay this check as long as possible. Once we detect we are in that
13265  // scenario, we just return.
13266  if (CC.isInvalid())
13267  return;
13268 
13269  if (Source->isAtomicType())
13270  S.Diag(E->getExprLoc(), diag::warn_atomic_implicit_seq_cst);
13271 
13272  // Diagnose implicit casts to bool.
13273  if (Target->isSpecificBuiltinType(BuiltinType::Bool)) {
13274  if (isa<StringLiteral>(E))
13275  // Warn on string literal to bool. Checks for string literals in logical
13276  // and expressions, for instance, assert(0 && "error here"), are
13277  // prevented by a check in AnalyzeImplicitConversions().
13278  return DiagnoseImpCast(S, E, T, CC,
13279  diag::warn_impcast_string_literal_to_bool);
13280  if (isa<ObjCStringLiteral>(E) || isa<ObjCArrayLiteral>(E) ||
13281  isa<ObjCDictionaryLiteral>(E) || isa<ObjCBoxedExpr>(E)) {
13282  // This covers the literal expressions that evaluate to Objective-C
13283  // objects.
13284  return DiagnoseImpCast(S, E, T, CC,
13285  diag::warn_impcast_objective_c_literal_to_bool);
13286  }
13287  if (Source->isPointerType() || Source->canDecayToPointerType()) {
13288  // Warn on pointer to bool conversion that is always true.
13289  S.DiagnoseAlwaysNonNullPointer(E, Expr::NPCK_NotNull, /*IsEqual*/ false,
13290  SourceRange(CC));
13291  }
13292  }
13293 
13294  // If the we're converting a constant to an ObjC BOOL on a platform where BOOL
13295  // is a typedef for signed char (macOS), then that constant value has to be 1
13296  // or 0.
13297  if (isObjCSignedCharBool(S, T) && Source->isIntegralType(S.Context)) {
13298  Expr::EvalResult Result;
13299  if (E->EvaluateAsInt(Result, S.getASTContext(),
13300  Expr::SE_AllowSideEffects)) {
13301  if (Result.Val.getInt() != 1 && Result.Val.getInt() != 0) {
13302  adornObjCBoolConversionDiagWithTernaryFixit(
13303  S, E,
13304  S.Diag(CC, diag::warn_impcast_constant_value_to_objc_bool)
13305  << toString(Result.Val.getInt(), 10));
13306  }
13307  return;
13308  }
13309  }
13310 
13311  // Check implicit casts from Objective-C collection literals to specialized
13312  // collection types, e.g., NSArray<NSString *> *.
13313  if (auto *ArrayLiteral = dyn_cast<ObjCArrayLiteral>(E))
13314  checkObjCArrayLiteral(S, QualType(Target, 0), ArrayLiteral);
13315  else if (auto *DictionaryLiteral = dyn_cast<ObjCDictionaryLiteral>(E))
13316  checkObjCDictionaryLiteral(S, QualType(Target, 0), DictionaryLiteral);
13317 
13318  // Strip vector types.
13319  if (isa<VectorType>(Source)) {
13320  if (Target->isVLSTBuiltinType() &&
13321  (S.Context.areCompatibleSveTypes(QualType(Target, 0),
13322  QualType(Source, 0)) ||
13323  S.Context.areLaxCompatibleSveTypes(QualType(Target, 0),
13324  QualType(Source, 0))))
13325  return;
13326 
13327  if (!isa<VectorType>(Target)) {
13328  if (S.SourceMgr.isInSystemMacro(CC))
13329  return;
13330  return DiagnoseImpCast(S, E, T, CC, diag::warn_impcast_vector_scalar);
13331  }
13332 
13333  // If the vector cast is cast between two vectors of the same size, it is
13334  // a bitcast, not a conversion.
13335  if (S.Context.getTypeSize(Source) == S.Context.getTypeSize(Target))
13336  return;
13337 
13338  Source = cast<VectorType>(Source)->getElementType().getTypePtr();
13339  Target = cast<VectorType>(Target)->getElementType().getTypePtr();
13340  }
13341  if (auto VecTy = dyn_cast<VectorType>(Target))
13342  Target = VecTy->getElementType().getTypePtr();
13343 
13344  // Strip complex types.
13345  if (isa<ComplexType>(Source)) {
13346  if (!isa<ComplexType>(Target)) {
13347  if (S.SourceMgr.isInSystemMacro(CC) || Target->isBooleanType())
13348  return;
13349 
13350  return DiagnoseImpCast(S, E, T, CC,
13351  S.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus
13352  ? diag::err_impcast_complex_scalar
13353  : diag::warn_impcast_complex_scalar);
13354  }
13355 
13356  Source = cast<ComplexType>(Source)->getElementType().getTypePtr();
13357  Target = cast<ComplexType>(Target)->getElementType().getTypePtr();
13358  }
13359 
13360  const BuiltinType *SourceBT = dyn_cast<BuiltinType>(Source);
13361  const BuiltinType *TargetBT = dyn_cast<BuiltinType>(Target);
13362 
13363  // If the source is floating point...
13364  if (SourceBT && SourceBT->isFloatingPoint()) {
13365  // ...and the target is floating point...
13366  if (TargetBT && TargetBT->isFloatingPoint()) {
13367  // ...then warn if we're dropping FP rank.
13368 
13369  int Order = S.getASTContext().getFloatingTypeSemanticOrder(
13370  QualType(SourceBT, 0), QualType(TargetBT, 0));
13371  if (Order > 0) {
13372  // Don't warn about float constants that are precisely
13373  // representable in the target type.
13374  Expr::EvalResult result;
13375  if (E->EvaluateAsRValue(result, S.Context)) {
13376  // Value might be a float, a float vector, or a float complex.
13377  if (IsSameFloatAfterCast(result.Val,
13378  S.Context.getFloatTypeSemantics(QualType(TargetBT, 0)),
13379  S.Context.getFloatTypeSemantics(QualType(SourceBT, 0))))
13380  return;
13381  }
13382 
13383  if (S.SourceMgr.isInSystemMacro(CC))
13384  return;
13385 
13386  DiagnoseImpCast(S, E, T, CC, diag::warn_impcast_float_precision);
13387  }
13388  // ... or possibly if we're increasing rank, too
13389  else if (Order < 0) {
13390  if (S.SourceMgr.isInSystemMacro(CC))
13391  return;
13392 
13393  DiagnoseImpCast(S, E, T, CC, diag::warn_impcast_double_promotion);
13394  }
13395  return;
13396  }
13397 
13398  // If the target is integral, always warn.
13399  if (TargetBT && TargetBT->isInteger()) {
13400  if (S.SourceMgr.isInSystemMacro(CC))
13401  return;
13402 
13403  DiagnoseFloatingImpCast(S, E, T, CC);
13404  }
13405 
13406  // Detect the case where a call result is converted from floating-point to
13407  // to bool, and the final argument to the call is converted from bool, to
13408  // discover this typo:
13409  //
13410  // bool b = fabs(x < 1.0); // should be "bool b = fabs(x) < 1.0;"
13411  //
13412  // FIXME: This is an incredibly special case; is there some more general
13413  // way to detect this class of misplaced-parentheses bug?
13414  if (Target->isBooleanType() && isa<CallExpr>(E)) {
13415  // Check last argument of function call to see if it is an
13416  // implicit cast from a type matching the type the result
13417  // is being cast to.
13418  CallExpr *CEx = cast<CallExpr>(E);
13419  if (unsigned NumArgs = CEx->getNumArgs()) {
13420  Expr *LastA = CEx->getArg(NumArgs - 1);
13421  Expr *InnerE = LastA->IgnoreParenImpCasts();
13422  if (isa<ImplicitCastExpr>(LastA) &&
13423  InnerE->getType()->isBooleanType()) {
13424  // Warn on this floating-point to bool conversion
13425  DiagnoseImpCast(S, E, T, CC,
13426  diag::warn_impcast_floating_point_to_bool);
13427  }
13428  }
13429  }
13430  return;
13431  }
13432 
13433  // Valid casts involving fixed point types should be accounted for here.
13434  if (Source->isFixedPointType()) {
13435  if (Target->isUnsaturatedFixedPointType()) {
13436  Expr::EvalResult Result;
13437  if (E->EvaluateAsFixedPoint(Result, S.Context, Expr::SE_AllowSideEffects,
13438  S.isConstantEvaluated())) {
13439  llvm::APFixedPoint Value = Result.Val.getFixedPoint();
13440  llvm::APFixedPoint MaxVal = S.Context.getFixedPointMax(T);
13441  llvm::APFixedPoint MinVal = S.Context.getFixedPointMin(T);
13442  if (Value > MaxVal || Value < MinVal) {
13443  S.DiagRuntimeBehavior(E->getExprLoc(), E,
13444  S.PDiag(diag::warn_impcast_fixed_point_range)
13445  << Value.toString() << T
13446  << E->getSourceRange()
13447  << clang::SourceRange(CC));
13448  return;
13449  }
13450  }
13451  } else if (Target->isIntegerType()) {
13452  Expr::EvalResult Result;
13453  if (!S.isConstantEvaluated() &&
13454  E->EvaluateAsFixedPoint(Result, S.Context,
13455  Expr::SE_AllowSideEffects)) {
13456  llvm::APFixedPoint FXResult = Result.Val.getFixedPoint();
13457 
13458  bool Overflowed;
13459  llvm::APSInt IntResult = FXResult.convertToInt(
13460  S.Context.getIntWidth(T),
13461  Target->isSignedIntegerOrEnumerationType(), &Overflowed);
13462 
13463  if (Overflowed) {
13464  S.DiagRuntimeBehavior(E->getExprLoc(), E,
13465  S.PDiag(diag::warn_impcast_fixed_point_range)
13466  << FXResult.toString() << T
13467  << E->getSourceRange()
13468  << clang::SourceRange(CC));
13469  return;
13470  }
13471  }
13472  }
13473  } else if (Target->isUnsaturatedFixedPointType()) {
13474  if (Source->isIntegerType()) {
13475  Expr::EvalResult Result;
13476  if (!S.isConstantEvaluated() &&
13477  E->EvaluateAsInt(Result, S.Context, Expr::SE_AllowSideEffects)) {
13478  llvm::APSInt Value = Result.Val.getInt();
13479 
13480  bool Overflowed;
13481  llvm::APFixedPoint IntResult = llvm::APFixedPoint::getFromIntValue(
13482  Value, S.Context.getFixedPointSemantics(T), &Overflowed);
13483 
13484  if (Overflowed) {
13485  S.DiagRuntimeBehavior(E->getExprLoc(), E,
13486  S.PDiag(diag::warn_impcast_fixed_point_range)
13487  << toString(Value, /*Radix=*/10) << T
13488  << E->getSourceRange()
13489  << clang::SourceRange(CC));
13490  return;
