13491  }
13492  }
13493  }
13494  }
13495 
13496  // If we are casting an integer type to a floating point type without
13497  // initialization-list syntax, we might lose accuracy if the floating
13498  // point type has a narrower significand than the integer type.
13499  if (SourceBT && TargetBT && SourceBT->isIntegerType() &&
13500  TargetBT->isFloatingType() && !IsListInit) {
13501  // Determine the number of precision bits in the source integer type.
13502  IntRange SourceRange = GetExprRange(S.Context, E, S.isConstantEvaluated(),
13503  /*Approximate*/ true);
13504  unsigned int SourcePrecision = SourceRange.Width;
13505 
13506  // Determine the number of precision bits in the
13507  // target floating point type.
13508  unsigned int TargetPrecision = llvm::APFloatBase::semanticsPrecision(
13509  S.Context.getFloatTypeSemantics(QualType(TargetBT, 0)));
13510 
13511  if (SourcePrecision > 0 && TargetPrecision > 0 &&
13512  SourcePrecision > TargetPrecision) {
13513 
13514  if (Optional<llvm::APSInt> SourceInt =
13515  E->getIntegerConstantExpr(S.Context)) {
13516  // If the source integer is a constant, convert it to the target
13517  // floating point type. Issue a warning if the value changes
13518  // during the whole conversion.
13519  llvm::APFloat TargetFloatValue(
13520  S.Context.getFloatTypeSemantics(QualType(TargetBT, 0)));
13521  llvm::APFloat::opStatus ConversionStatus =
13522  TargetFloatValue.convertFromAPInt(
13523  *SourceInt, SourceBT->isSignedInteger(),
13524  llvm::APFloat::rmNearestTiesToEven);
13525 
13526  if (ConversionStatus != llvm::APFloat::opOK) {
13527  SmallString<32> PrettySourceValue;
13528  SourceInt->toString(PrettySourceValue, 10);
13529  SmallString<32> PrettyTargetValue;
13530  TargetFloatValue.toString(PrettyTargetValue, TargetPrecision);
13531 
13532  S.DiagRuntimeBehavior(
13533  E->getExprLoc(), E,
13534  S.PDiag(diag::warn_impcast_integer_float_precision_constant)
13535  << PrettySourceValue << PrettyTargetValue << E->getType() << T
13536  << E->getSourceRange() << clang::SourceRange(CC));
13537  }
13538  } else {
13539  // Otherwise, the implicit conversion may lose precision.
13540  DiagnoseImpCast(S, E, T, CC,
13541  diag::warn_impcast_integer_float_precision);
13542  }
13543  }
13544  }
13545 
13546  DiagnoseNullConversion(S, E, T, CC);
13547 
13548  S.DiscardMisalignedMemberAddress(Target, E);
13549 
13550  if (Target->isBooleanType())
13551  DiagnoseIntInBoolContext(S, E);
13552 
13553  if (!Source->isIntegerType() || !Target->isIntegerType())
13554  return;
13555 
13556  // TODO: remove this early return once the false positives for constant->bool
13557  // in templates, macros, etc, are reduced or removed.
13558  if (Target->isSpecificBuiltinType(BuiltinType::Bool))
13559  return;
13560 
13561  if (isObjCSignedCharBool(S, T) && !Source->isCharType() &&
13562  !E->isKnownToHaveBooleanValue(/*Semantic=*/false)) {
13563  return adornObjCBoolConversionDiagWithTernaryFixit(
13564  S, E,
13565  S.Diag(CC, diag::warn_impcast_int_to_objc_signed_char_bool)
13566  << E->getType());
13567  }
13568 
13569  IntRange SourceTypeRange =
13570  IntRange::forTargetOfCanonicalType(S.Context, Source);
13571  IntRange LikelySourceRange =
13572  GetExprRange(S.Context, E, S.isConstantEvaluated(), /*Approximate*/ true);
13573  IntRange TargetRange = IntRange::forTargetOfCanonicalType(S.Context, Target);
13574 
13575  if (LikelySourceRange.Width > TargetRange.Width) {
13576  // If the source is a constant, use a default-on diagnostic.
13577  // TODO: this should happen for bitfield stores, too.
13578  Expr::EvalResult Result;
13579  if (E->EvaluateAsInt(Result, S.Context, Expr::SE_AllowSideEffects,
13580  S.isConstantEvaluated())) {
13581  llvm::APSInt Value(32);
13582  Value = Result.Val.getInt();
13583 
13584  if (S.SourceMgr.isInSystemMacro(CC))
13585  return;
13586 
13587  std::string PrettySourceValue = toString(Value, 10);
13588  std::string PrettyTargetValue = PrettyPrintInRange(Value, TargetRange);
13589 
13590  S.DiagRuntimeBehavior(
13591  E->getExprLoc(), E,
13592  S.PDiag(diag::warn_impcast_integer_precision_constant)
13593  << PrettySourceValue << PrettyTargetValue << E->getType() << T
13594  << E->getSourceRange() << SourceRange(CC));
13595  return;
13596  }
13597 
13598  // People want to build with -Wshorten-64-to-32 and not -Wconversion.
13599  if (S.SourceMgr.isInSystemMacro(CC))
13600  return;
13601 
13602  if (TargetRange.Width == 32 && S.Context.getIntWidth(E->getType()) == 64)
13603  return DiagnoseImpCast(S, E, T, CC, diag::warn_impcast_integer_64_32,
13604  /* pruneControlFlow */ true);
13605  return DiagnoseImpCast(S, E, T, CC, diag::warn_impcast_integer_precision);
13606  }
13607 
13608  if (TargetRange.Width > SourceTypeRange.Width) {
13609  if (auto *UO = dyn_cast<UnaryOperator>(E))
13610  if (UO->getOpcode() == UO_Minus)
13611  if (Source->isUnsignedIntegerType()) {
13612  if (Target->isUnsignedIntegerType())
13613  return DiagnoseImpCast(S, E, T, CC,
13614  diag::warn_impcast_high_order_zero_bits);
13615  if (Target->isSignedIntegerType())
13616  return DiagnoseImpCast(S, E, T, CC,
13617  diag::warn_impcast_nonnegative_result);
13618  }
13619  }
13620 
13621  if (TargetRange.Width == LikelySourceRange.Width &&
13622  !TargetRange.NonNegative && LikelySourceRange.NonNegative &&
13623  Source->isSignedIntegerType()) {
13624  // Warn when doing a signed to signed conversion, warn if the positive
13625  // source value is exactly the width of the target type, which will
13626  // cause a negative value to be stored.
13627 
13628  Expr::EvalResult Result;
13629  if (E->EvaluateAsInt(Result, S.Context, Expr::SE_AllowSideEffects) &&
13630  !S.SourceMgr.isInSystemMacro(CC)) {
13631  llvm::APSInt Value = Result.Val.getInt();
13632  if (isSameWidthConstantConversion(S, E, T, CC)) {
13633  std::string PrettySourceValue = toString(Value, 10);
13634  std::string PrettyTargetValue = PrettyPrintInRange(Value, TargetRange);
13635 
13636  S.DiagRuntimeBehavior(
13637  E->getExprLoc(), E,
13638  S.PDiag(diag::warn_impcast_integer_precision_constant)
13639  << PrettySourceValue << PrettyTargetValue << E->getType() << T
13640  << E->getSourceRange() << SourceRange(CC));
13641  return;
13642  }
13643  }
13644 
13645  // Fall through for non-constants to give a sign conversion warning.
13646  }
13647 
13648  if ((TargetRange.NonNegative && !LikelySourceRange.NonNegative) ||
13649  (!TargetRange.NonNegative && LikelySourceRange.NonNegative &&
13650  LikelySourceRange.Width == TargetRange.Width)) {
13651  if (S.SourceMgr.isInSystemMacro(CC))
13652  return;
13653 
13654  unsigned DiagID = diag::warn_impcast_integer_sign;
13655 
13656  // Traditionally, gcc has warned about this under -Wsign-compare.
13657  // We also want to warn about it in -Wconversion.
13658  // So if -Wconversion is off, use a completely identical diagnostic
13659  // in the sign-compare group.
13660  // The conditional-checking code will
13661  if (ICContext) {
13662  DiagID = diag::warn_impcast_integer_sign_conditional;
13663  *ICContext = true;
13664  }
13665 
13666  return DiagnoseImpCast(S, E, T, CC, DiagID);
13667  }
13668 
13669  // Diagnose conversions between different enumeration types.
13670  // In C, we pretend that the type of an EnumConstantDecl is its enumeration
13671  // type, to give us better diagnostics.
13672  QualType SourceType = E->getType();
13673  if (!S.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus) {
13674  if (DeclRefExpr *DRE = dyn_cast<DeclRefExpr>(E))
13675  if (EnumConstantDecl *ECD = dyn_cast<EnumConstantDecl>(DRE->getDecl())) {
13676  EnumDecl *Enum = cast<EnumDecl>(ECD->getDeclContext());
13677  SourceType = S.Context.getTypeDeclType(Enum);
13678  Source = S.Context.getCanonicalType(SourceType).getTypePtr();
13679  }
13680  }
13681 
13682  if (const EnumType *SourceEnum = Source->getAs<EnumType>())
13683  if (const EnumType *TargetEnum = Target->getAs<EnumType>())
13684  if (SourceEnum->getDecl()->hasNameForLinkage() &&
13685  TargetEnum->getDecl()->hasNameForLinkage() &&
13686  SourceEnum != TargetEnum) {
13687  if (S.SourceMgr.isInSystemMacro(CC))
13688  return;
13689 
13690  return DiagnoseImpCast(S, E, SourceType, T, CC,
13691  diag::warn_impcast_different_enum_types);
13692  }
13693 }
13694 
13695 static void CheckConditionalOperator(Sema &S, AbstractConditionalOperator *E,
13696  SourceLocation CC, QualType T);
13697 
13698 static void CheckConditionalOperand(Sema &S, Expr *E, QualType T,
13699  SourceLocation CC, bool &ICContext) {
13700  E = E->IgnoreParenImpCasts();
13701 
13702  if (auto *CO = dyn_cast<AbstractConditionalOperator>(E))
13703  return CheckConditionalOperator(S, CO, CC, T);
13704 
13705  AnalyzeImplicitConversions(S, E, CC);
13706  if (E->getType() != T)
13707  return CheckImplicitConversion(S, E, T, CC, &ICContext);
13708 }
13709 
13710 static void CheckConditionalOperator(Sema &S, AbstractConditionalOperator *E,
13711  SourceLocation CC, QualType T) {
13712  AnalyzeImplicitConversions(S, E->getCond(), E->getQuestionLoc());
13713 
13714  Expr *TrueExpr = E->getTrueExpr();
13715  if (auto *BCO = dyn_cast<BinaryConditionalOperator>(E))
13716  TrueExpr = BCO->getCommon();
13717 
13718  bool Suspicious = false;
13719  CheckConditionalOperand(S, TrueExpr, T, CC, Suspicious);
13720  CheckConditionalOperand(S, E->getFalseExpr(), T, CC, Suspicious);
13721 
13722  if (T->isBooleanType())
13723  DiagnoseIntInBoolContext(S, E);
13724 
13725  // If -Wconversion would have warned about either of the candidates
13726  // for a signedness conversion to the context type...
13727  if (!Suspicious) return;
13728 
13729  // ...but it's currently ignored...
13730  if (!S.Diags.isIgnored(diag::warn_impcast_integer_sign_conditional, CC))
13731  return;
13732 
13733  // ...then check whether it would have warned about either of the
13734  // candidates for a signedness conversion to the condition type.
13735  if (E->getType() == T) return;
13736 
13737  Suspicious = false;
13738  CheckImplicitConversion(S, TrueExpr->IgnoreParenImpCasts(),
13739  E->getType(), CC, &Suspicious);
13740  if (!Suspicious)
13741  CheckImplicitConversion(S, E->getFalseExpr()->IgnoreParenImpCasts(),
13742  E->getType(), CC, &Suspicious);
13743 }
13744 
13745 /// Check conversion of given expression to boolean.
13746 /// Input argument E is a logical expression.
13747 static void CheckBoolLikeConversion(Sema &S, Expr *E, SourceLocation CC) {
13748  if (S.getLangOpts().Bool)
13749  return;
13750  if (E->IgnoreParenImpCasts()->getType()->isAtomicType())
13751  return;
13752  CheckImplicitConversion(S, E->IgnoreParenImpCasts(), S.Context.BoolTy, CC);
13753 }
13754 
13755 namespace {
13756 struct AnalyzeImplicitConversionsWorkItem {
13757  Expr *E;
13758  SourceLocation CC;
13759  bool IsListInit;
13760 };
13761 }
13762 
13763 /// Data recursive variant of AnalyzeImplicitConversions. Subexpressions
13764 /// that should be visited are added to WorkList.
13765 static void AnalyzeImplicitConversions(
13766  Sema &S, AnalyzeImplicitConversionsWorkItem Item,
13767  llvm::SmallVectorImpl<AnalyzeImplicitConversionsWorkItem> &WorkList) {
13768  Expr *OrigE = Item.E;
13769  SourceLocation CC = Item.CC;
13770 
13771  QualType T = OrigE->getType();
13772  Expr *E = OrigE->IgnoreParenImpCasts();
13773 
13774  // Propagate whether we are in a C++ list initialization expression.
13775  // If so, we do not issue warnings for implicit int-float conversion
13776  // precision loss, because C++11 narrowing already handles it.
13777  bool IsListInit = Item.IsListInit ||
13778  (isa<InitListExpr>(OrigE) && S.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus);
13779 
13780  if (E->isTypeDependent() || E->isValueDependent())
13781  return;
13782 
13783  Expr *SourceExpr = E;
13784  // Examine, but don't traverse into the source expression of an
13785  // OpaqueValueExpr, since it may have multiple parents and we don't want to
13786  // emit duplicate diagnostics. Its fine to examine the form or attempt to
13787  // evaluate it in the context of checking the specific conversion to T though.
13788  if (auto *OVE = dyn_cast<OpaqueValueExpr>(E))
13789  if (auto *Src = OVE->getSourceExpr())
13790  SourceExpr = Src;
13791 
13792  if (const auto *UO = dyn_cast<UnaryOperator>(SourceExpr))
13793  if (UO->getOpcode() == UO_Not &&
13794  UO->getSubExpr()->isKnownToHaveBooleanValue())
13795  S.Diag(UO->getBeginLoc(), diag::warn_bitwise_negation_bool)
13796  << OrigE->getSourceRange() << T->isBooleanType()
13797  << FixItHint::CreateReplacement(UO->getBeginLoc(), "!");
13798 
13799  if (const auto *BO = dyn_cast<BinaryOperator>(SourceExpr))
13800  if ((BO->getOpcode() == BO_And || BO->getOpcode() == BO_Or) &&
13801  BO->getLHS()->isKnownToHaveBooleanValue() &&
13802  BO->getRHS()->isKnownToHaveBooleanValue() &&
13803  BO->getLHS()->HasSideEffects(S.Context) &&
13804  BO->getRHS()->HasSideEffects(S.Context)) {
13805  S.Diag(BO->getBeginLoc(), diag::warn_bitwise_instead_of_logical)
13806  << (BO->getOpcode() == BO_And ? "&" : "|") << OrigE->getSourceRange()
13807  << FixItHint::CreateReplacement(
13808  BO->getOperatorLoc(),
13809  (BO->getOpcode() == BO_And ? "&&" : "||"));
13810  S.Diag(BO->getBeginLoc(), diag::note_cast_operand_to_int);
13811  }
13812 
13813  // For conditional operators, we analyze the arguments as if they
13814  // were being fed directly into the output.
13815  if (auto *CO = dyn_cast<AbstractConditionalOperator>(SourceExpr)) {
13816  CheckConditionalOperator(S, CO, CC, T);
13817  return;
13818  }
13819 
13820  // Check implicit argument conversions for function calls.
13821  if (CallExpr *Call = dyn_cast<CallExpr>(SourceExpr))
13822  CheckImplicitArgumentConversions(S, Call, CC);
13823 
13824  // Go ahead and check any implicit conversions we might have skipped.
13825  // The non-canonical typecheck is just an optimization;
13826  // CheckImplicitConversion will filter out dead implicit conversions.
13827  if (SourceExpr->getType() != T)
13828  CheckImplicitConversion(S, SourceExpr, T, CC, nullptr, IsListInit);
13829 
13830  // Now continue drilling into this expression.
13831 
13832  if (PseudoObjectExpr *POE = dyn_cast<PseudoObjectExpr>(E)) {
13833  // The bound subexpressions in a PseudoObjectExpr are not reachable
13834  // as transitive children.
13835  // FIXME: Use a more uniform representation for this.
13836  for (auto *SE : POE->semantics())
13837  if (auto *OVE = dyn_cast<OpaqueValueExpr>(SE))
13838  WorkList.push_back({OVE->getSourceExpr(), CC, IsListInit});
13839  }
13840 
13841  // Skip past explicit casts.
13842  if (auto *CE = dyn_cast<ExplicitCastExpr>(E)) {
13843  E = CE->getSubExpr()->IgnoreParenImpCasts();
13844  if (!CE->getType()->isVoidType() && E->getType()->isAtomicType())
13845  S.Diag(E->getBeginLoc(), diag::warn_atomic_implicit_seq_cst);
13846  WorkList.push_back({E, CC, IsListInit});
13847  return;
13848  }
13849 
13850  if (BinaryOperator *BO = dyn_cast<BinaryOperator>(E)) {
13851  // Do a somewhat different check with comparison operators.
13852  if (BO->isComparisonOp())
13853  return AnalyzeComparison(S, BO);
13854 
13855  // And with simple assignments.
13856  if (BO->getOpcode() == BO_Assign)
13857  return AnalyzeAssignment(S, BO);
13858  // And with compound assignments.
13859  if (BO->isAssignmentOp())
13860  return AnalyzeCompoundAssignment(S, BO);
13861  }
13862 
13863  // These break the otherwise-useful invariant below. Fortunately,
13864  // we don't really need to recurse into them, because any internal
13865  // expressions should have been analyzed already when they were
13866  // built into statements.
13867  if (isa<StmtExpr>(E)) return;
13868 
13869  // Don't descend into unevaluated contexts.
13870  if (isa<UnaryExprOrTypeTraitExpr>(E)) return;
13871 
13872  // Now just recurse over the expression's children.
13873  CC = E->getExprLoc();
13874  BinaryOperator *BO = dyn_cast<BinaryOperator>(E);
13875  bool IsLogicalAndOperator = BO && BO->getOpcode() == BO_LAnd;
13876  for (Stmt *SubStmt : E->children()) {
13877  Expr *ChildExpr = dyn_cast_or_null<Expr>(SubStmt);
13878  if (!ChildExpr)
13879  continue;
13880 
13881  if (IsLogicalAndOperator &&
13882  isa<StringLiteral>(ChildExpr->IgnoreParenImpCasts()))
13883  // Ignore checking string literals that are in logical and operators.
13884  // This is a common pattern for asserts.
13885  continue;
13886  WorkList.push_back({ChildExpr, CC, IsListInit});
13887  }
13888 
13889  if (BO && BO->isLogicalOp()) {
13890  Expr *SubExpr = BO->getLHS()->IgnoreParenImpCasts();
13891  if (!IsLogicalAndOperator || !isa<StringLiteral>(SubExpr))
13892  ::CheckBoolLikeConversion(S, SubExpr, BO->getExprLoc());
13893 
13894  SubExpr = BO->getRHS()->IgnoreParenImpCasts();
13895  if (!IsLogicalAndOperator || !isa<StringLiteral>(SubExpr))
13896  ::CheckBoolLikeConversion(S, SubExpr, BO->getExprLoc());
13897  }
13898 
13899  if (const UnaryOperator *U = dyn_cast<UnaryOperator>(E)) {
13900  if (U->getOpcode() == UO_LNot) {
13901  ::CheckBoolLikeConversion(S, U->getSubExpr(), CC);
13902  } else if (U->getOpcode() != UO_AddrOf) {
13903  if (U->getSubExpr()->getType()->isAtomicType())
13904  S.Diag(U->getSubExpr()->getBeginLoc(),
13905  diag::warn_atomic_implicit_seq_cst);
13906  }
13907  }
13908 }
13909 
13910 /// AnalyzeImplicitConversions - Find and report any interesting
13911 /// implicit conversions in the given expression. There are a couple
13912 /// of competing diagnostics here, -Wconversion and -Wsign-compare.
13913 static void AnalyzeImplicitConversions(Sema &S, Expr *OrigE, SourceLocation CC,
13914  bool IsListInit/*= false*/) {
13915  llvm::SmallVector<AnalyzeImplicitConversionsWorkItem, 16> WorkList;
13916  WorkList.push_back({OrigE, CC, IsListInit});
13917  while (!WorkList.empty())
13918  AnalyzeImplicitConversions(S, WorkList.pop_back_val(), WorkList);
13919 }
13920 
13921 /// Diagnose integer type and any valid implicit conversion to it.
13922 static bool checkOpenCLEnqueueIntType(Sema &S, Expr *E, const QualType &IntT) {
13923  // Taking into account implicit conversions,
13924  // allow any integer.
13925  if (!E->getType()->isIntegerType()) {
13926  S.Diag(E->getBeginLoc(),
13927  diag::err_opencl_enqueue_kernel_invalid_local_size_type);
13928  return true;
13929  }
13930  // Potentially emit standard warnings for implicit conversions if enabled
13931  // using -Wconversion.
13932  CheckImplicitConversion(S, E, IntT, E->getBeginLoc());
13933  return false;
13934 }
13935 
13936 // Helper function for Sema::DiagnoseAlwaysNonNullPointer.
13937 // Returns true when emitting a warning about taking the address of a reference.
13938 static bool CheckForReference(Sema &SemaRef, const Expr *E,
13939  const PartialDiagnostic &PD) {
13940  E = E->IgnoreParenImpCasts();
13941 
13942  const FunctionDecl *FD = nullptr;
13943 
13944  if (const DeclRefExpr *DRE = dyn_cast<DeclRefExpr>(E)) {
13945  if (!DRE->getDecl()->getType()->isReferenceType())
13946  return false;
13947  } else if (const MemberExpr *M = dyn_cast<MemberExpr>(E)) {
13948  if (!M->getMemberDecl()->getType()->isReferenceType())
13949  return false;
13950  } else if (const CallExpr *Call = dyn_cast<CallExpr>(E)) {
13951  if (!Call->getCallReturnType(SemaRef.Context)->isReferenceType())
13952  return false;
13953  FD = Call->getDirectCallee();
13954  } else {
13955  return false;
13956  }
13957 
13958  SemaRef.Diag(E->getExprLoc(), PD);
13959 
13960  // If possible, point to location of function.
13961  if (FD) {
13962  SemaRef.Diag(FD->getLocation(), diag::note_reference_is_return_value) << FD;
13963  }
13964 
13965  return true;
13966 }
13967 
13968 // Returns true if the SourceLocation is expanded from any macro body.
13969 // Returns false if the SourceLocation is invalid, is from not in a macro
13970 // expansion, or is from expanded from a top-level macro argument.
13971 static bool IsInAnyMacroBody(const SourceManager &SM, SourceLocation Loc) {
13972  if (Loc.isInvalid())
13973  return false;
13974 
13975  while (Loc.isMacroID()) {
13976  if (SM.isMacroBodyExpansion(Loc))
13977  return true;
13978  Loc = SM.getImmediateMacroCallerLoc(Loc);
13979  }
13980 
13981  return false;
13982 }
13983 
13984 /// Diagnose pointers that are always non-null.
13985 /// \param E the expression containing the pointer
13986 /// \param NullKind NPCK_NotNull if E is a cast to bool, otherwise, E is
13987 /// compared to a null pointer
13988 /// \param IsEqual True when the comparison is equal to a null pointer
13989 /// \param Range Extra SourceRange to highlight in the diagnostic
13990 void Sema::DiagnoseAlwaysNonNullPointer(Expr *E,
13991  Expr::NullPointerConstantKind NullKind,
13992  bool IsEqual, SourceRange Range) {
13993  if (!E)
13994  return;
13995 
13996  // Don't warn inside macros.
13997  if (E->getExprLoc().isMacroID()) {
13998  const SourceManager &SM = getSourceManager();
13999  if (IsInAnyMacroBody(SM, E->getExprLoc()) ||
14000  IsInAnyMacroBody(SM, Range.getBegin()))
14001  return;
14002  }
14003  E = E->IgnoreImpCasts();
14004 
14005  const bool IsCompare = NullKind != Expr::NPCK_NotNull;
14006 
14007  if (isa<CXXThisExpr>(E)) {
14008  unsigned DiagID = IsCompare ? diag::warn_this_null_compare
14009  : diag::warn_this_bool_conversion;
14010  Diag(E->getExprLoc(), DiagID) << E->getSourceRange() << Range << IsEqual;
14011  return;
14012  }
14013 
14014  bool IsAddressOf = false;
14015 
14016  if (UnaryOperator *UO = dyn_cast<UnaryOperator>(E)) {
14017  if (UO->getOpcode() != UO_AddrOf)
14018  return;
14019  IsAddressOf = true;
14020  E = UO->getSubExpr();
14021  }
14022 
14023  if (IsAddressOf) {
14024  unsigned DiagID = IsCompare
14025  ? diag::warn_address_of_reference_null_compare
14026  : diag::warn_address_of_reference_bool_conversion;
14027  PartialDiagnostic PD = PDiag(DiagID) << E->getSourceRange() << Range
14028  << IsEqual;
14029  if (CheckForReference(*this, E, PD)) {
14030  return;
14031  }
14032  }
14033 
14034  auto ComplainAboutNonnullParamOrCall = [&](const Attr *NonnullAttr) {
14035  bool IsParam = isa<NonNullAttr>(NonnullAttr);
14036  std::string Str;
14037  llvm::raw_string_ostream S(Str);
14038  E->printPretty(S, nullptr, getPrintingPolicy());
14039  unsigned DiagID = IsCompare ? diag::warn_nonnull_expr_compare
14040  : diag::warn_cast_nonnull_to_bool;
14041  Diag(E->getExprLoc(), DiagID) << IsParam << S.str()
14042  << E->getSourceRange() << Range << IsEqual;
14043  Diag(NonnullAttr->getLocation(), diag::note_declared_nonnull) << IsParam;
14044  };
14045 
14046  // If we have a CallExpr that is tagged with returns_nonnull, we can complain.
14047  if (auto *Call = dyn_cast<CallExpr>(E->IgnoreParenImpCasts())) {
14048  if (auto *Callee = Call->getDirectCallee()) {
14049  if (const Attr *A = Callee->getAttr<ReturnsNonNullAttr>()) {
14050  ComplainAboutNonnullParamOrCall(A);
14051  return;
14052  }
14053  }
14054  }
14055 
14056  // Expect to find a single Decl. Skip anything more complicated.
14057  ValueDecl *D = nullptr;
14058  if (DeclRefExpr *R = dyn_cast<DeclRefExpr>(E)) {
14059  D = R->getDecl();
14060  } else if (MemberExpr *M = dyn_cast<MemberExpr>(E)) {
14061  D = M->getMemberDecl();
14062  }
14063 
14064  // Weak Decls can be null.
14065  if (!D || D->isWeak())
14066  return;
14067 
14068  // Check for parameter decl with nonnull attribute
14069  if (const auto* PV = dyn_cast<ParmVarDecl>(D)) {
14070  if (getCurFunction() &&
14071  !getCurFunction()->ModifiedNonNullParams.count(PV)) {
14072  if (const Attr *A = PV->getAttr<NonNullAttr>()) {
14073  ComplainAboutNonnullParamOrCall(A);
14074  return;
14075  }
14076 
14077  if (const auto *FD = dyn_cast<FunctionDecl>(PV->getDeclContext())) {
14078  // Skip function template not specialized yet.
14079  if (FD->getTemplatedKind() == FunctionDecl::TK_FunctionTemplate)
14080  return;
14081  auto ParamIter = llvm::find(FD->parameters(), PV);
14082  assert(ParamIter != FD->param_end());
14083  unsigned ParamNo = std::distance(FD->param_begin(), ParamIter);
14084 
14085  for (const auto *NonNull : FD->specific_attrs<NonNullAttr>()) {
14086  if (!NonNull->args_size()) {
14087  ComplainAboutNonnullParamOrCall(NonNull);
14088  return;
14089  }
14090 
14091  for (const ParamIdx &ArgNo : NonNull->args()) {
14092  if (ArgNo.getASTIndex() == ParamNo) {
14093  ComplainAboutNonnullParamOrCall(NonNull);
14094  return;
14095  }
14096  }
14097  }
14098  }
14099  }
14100  }
14101 
14102  QualType T = D->getType();
14103  const bool IsArray = T->isArrayType();
14104  const bool IsFunction = T->isFunctionType();
14105 
14106  // Address of function is used to silence the function warning.
14107  if (IsAddressOf && IsFunction) {
14108  return;
14109  }
14110 
14111  // Found nothing.
14112  if (!IsAddressOf && !IsFunction && !IsArray)
14113  return;
14114 
14115  // Pretty print the expression for the diagnostic.
14116  std::string Str;
14117  llvm::raw_string_ostream S(Str);
14118  E->printPretty(S, nullptr, getPrintingPolicy());
14119 
14120  unsigned DiagID = IsCompare ? diag::warn_null_pointer_compare
14121  : diag::warn_impcast_pointer_to_bool;
14122  enum {
14123  AddressOf,
14124  FunctionPointer,
14125  ArrayPointer
14126  } DiagType;
14127  if (IsAddressOf)
14128  DiagType = AddressOf;
14129  else if (IsFunction)
14130  DiagType = FunctionPointer;
14131  else if (IsArray)
14132  DiagType = ArrayPointer;
14133  else
14134  llvm_unreachable("Could not determine diagnostic.");
14135  Diag(E->getExprLoc(), DiagID) << DiagType << S.str() << E->getSourceRange()
14136  << Range << IsEqual;
14137 
14138  if (!IsFunction)
14139  return;
14140 
14141  // Suggest '&' to silence the function warning.
14142  Diag(E->getExprLoc(), diag::note_function_warning_silence)
14143  << FixItHint::CreateInsertion(E->getBeginLoc(), "&");
14144 
14145  // Check to see if '()' fixit should be emitted.
14146  QualType ReturnType;
14147  UnresolvedSet<4> NonTemplateOverloads;
14148  tryExprAsCall(*E, ReturnType, NonTemplateOverloads);
14149  if (ReturnType.isNull())
14150  return;
14151 
14152  if (IsCompare) {
14153  // There are two cases here. If there is null constant, the only suggest
14154  // for a pointer return type. If the null is 0, then suggest if the return
14155  // type is a pointer or an integer type.
14156  if (!ReturnType->isPointerType()) {
14157  if (NullKind == Expr::NPCK_ZeroExpression ||
14158  NullKind == Expr::NPCK_ZeroLiteral) {
14159  if (!ReturnType->isIntegerType())
14160  return;
14161  } else {
14162  return;
14163  }
14164  }
14165  } else { // !IsCompare
14166  // For function to bool, only suggest if the function pointer has bool
14167  // return type.
14168  if (!ReturnType->isSpecificBuiltinType(BuiltinType::Bool))
14169  return;
14170  }
14171  Diag(E->getExprLoc(), diag::note_function_to_function_call)
14172  << FixItHint::CreateInsertion(getLocForEndOfToken(E->getEndLoc()), "()");
14173 }
14174 
14175 /// Diagnoses "dangerous" implicit conversions within the given
14176 /// expression (which is a full expression). Implements -Wconversion
14177 /// and -Wsign-compare.
14178 ///
14179 /// \param CC the "context" location of the implicit conversion, i.e.
14180 /// the most location of the syntactic entity requiring the implicit
14181 /// conversion
14182 void Sema::CheckImplicitConversions(Expr *E, SourceLocation CC) {
14183  // Don't diagnose in unevaluated contexts.
14184  if (isUnevaluatedContext())
14185  return;
14186 
14187  // Don't diagnose for value- or type-dependent expressions.
14188  if (E->isTypeDependent() || E->isValueDependent())
14189  return;
14190 
14191  // Check for array bounds violations in cases where the check isn't triggered
14192  // elsewhere for other Expr types (like BinaryOperators), e.g. when an
14193  // ArraySubscriptExpr is on the RHS of a variable initialization.
14194  CheckArrayAccess(E);
14195 
14196  // This is not the right CC for (e.g.) a variable initialization.
14197  AnalyzeImplicitConversions(*this, E, CC);
14198 }
14199 
14200 /// CheckBoolLikeConversion - Check conversion of given expression to boolean.
14201 /// Input argument E is a logical expression.
14202 void Sema::CheckBoolLikeConversion(Expr *E, SourceLocation CC) {
14203  ::CheckBoolLikeConversion(*this, E, CC);
14204 }
14205 
14206 /// Diagnose when expression is an integer constant expression and its evaluation
14207 /// results in integer overflow
14208 void Sema::CheckForIntOverflow (Expr *E) {
14209  // Use a work list to deal with nested struct initializers.
14210  SmallVector<Expr *, 2> Exprs(1, E);
14211 
14212  do {
14213  Expr *OriginalE = Exprs.pop_back_val();
14214  Expr *E = OriginalE->IgnoreParenCasts();
14215 
14216  if (isa<BinaryOperator>(E)) {
14217  E->EvaluateForOverflow(Context);
14218  continue;
14219  }
14220 
14221  if (auto InitList = dyn_cast<InitListExpr>(OriginalE))
14222  Exprs.append(InitList->inits().begin(), InitList->inits().end());
14223  else if (isa<ObjCBoxedExpr>(OriginalE))
14224  E->EvaluateForOverflow(Context);
14225  else if (auto Call = dyn_cast<CallExpr>(E))
14226  Exprs.append(Call->arg_begin(), Call->arg_end());
14227  else if (auto Message = dyn_cast<ObjCMessageExpr>(E))
14228  Exprs.append(Message->arg_begin(), Message->arg_end());
14229  } while (!Exprs.empty());
14230 }
14231 
14232 namespace {
14233 
14234 /// Visitor for expressions which looks for unsequenced operations on the
14235 /// same object.
14236 class SequenceChecker : public ConstEvaluatedExprVisitor<SequenceChecker> {
14237  using Base = ConstEvaluatedExprVisitor<SequenceChecker>;
14238 
14239  /// A tree of sequenced regions within an expression. Two regions are
14240  /// unsequenced if one is an ancestor or a descendent of the other. When we
14241  /// finish processing an expression with sequencing, such as a comma
14242  /// expression, we fold its tree nodes into its parent, since they are
14243  /// unsequenced with respect to nodes we will visit later.
14244  class SequenceTree {
14245  struct Value {
14246  explicit Value(unsigned Parent) : Parent(Parent), Merged(false) {}
14247  unsigned Parent : 31;
14248  unsigned Merged : 1;
14249  };
14250  SmallVector<Value, 8> Values;
14251 
14252  public:
14253  /// A region within an expression which may be sequenced with respect
14254  /// to some other region.
14255  class Seq {
14256  friend class SequenceTree;
14257 
14258  unsigned Index;
14259 
14260  explicit Seq(unsigned N) : Index(N) {}
14261 
14262  public:
14263  Seq() : Index(0) {}
14264  };
14265 
14266  SequenceTree() { Values.push_back(Value(0)); }
14267  Seq root() const { return Seq(0); }
14268 
14269  /// Create a new sequence of operations, which is an unsequenced
14270  /// subset of \p Parent. This sequence of operations is sequenced with
14271  /// respect to other children of \p Parent.
14272  Seq allocate(Seq Parent) {
14273  Values.push_back(Value(Parent.Index));
14274  return Seq(Values.size() - 1);
14275  }
14276 
14277  /// Merge a sequence of operations into its parent.
14278  void merge(Seq S) {
14279  Values[S.Index].Merged = true;
14280  }
14281 
14282  /// Determine whether two operations are unsequenced. This operation
14283  /// is asymmetric: \p Cur should be the more recent sequence, and \p Old
14284  /// should have been merged into its parent as appropriate.
14285  bool isUnsequenced(Seq Cur, Seq Old) {
14286  unsigned C = representative(Cur.Index);
14287  unsigned Target = representative(Old.Index);
14288  while (C >= Target) {
14289  if (C == Target)
14290  return true;
14291  C = Values[C].Parent;
14292  }
14293  return false;
14294  }
14295 
14296  private:
14297  /// Pick a representative for a sequence.
14298  unsigned representative(unsigned K) {
14299  if (Values[K].Merged)
14300  // Perform path compression as we go.
14301  return Values[K].Parent = representative(Values[K].Parent);
14302  return K;
14303  }
14304  };
14305 
14306  /// An object for which we can track unsequenced uses.
14307  using Object = const NamedDecl *;
14308 
14309  /// Different flavors of object usage which we track. We only track the
14310  /// least-sequenced usage of each kind.
14311  enum UsageKind {
14312  /// A read of an object. Multiple unsequenced reads are OK.
14313  UK_Use,
14314 
14315  /// A modification of an object which is sequenced before the value
14316  /// computation of the expression, such as ++n in C++.
14317  UK_ModAsValue,
14318 
14319  /// A modification of an object which is not sequenced before the value
14320  /// computation of the expression, such as n++.
14321  UK_ModAsSideEffect,
14322 
14323  UK_Count = UK_ModAsSideEffect + 1
14324  };
14325 
14326  /// Bundle together a sequencing region and the expression corresponding
14327  /// to a specific usage. One Usage is stored for each usage kind in UsageInfo.
14328  struct Usage {
14329  const Expr *UsageExpr;
14330  SequenceTree::Seq Seq;
14331 
14332  Usage() : UsageExpr(nullptr) {}
14333  };
14334 
14335  struct UsageInfo {
14336  Usage Uses[UK_Count];
14337 
14338  /// Have we issued a diagnostic for this object already?
14339  bool Diagnosed;
14340 
14341  UsageInfo() : Diagnosed(false) {}
14342  };
14343  using UsageInfoMap = llvm::SmallDenseMap<Object, UsageInfo, 16>;
14344 
14345  Sema &SemaRef;
14346 
14347  /// Sequenced regions within the expression.
14348  SequenceTree Tree;
14349 
14350  /// Declaration modifications and references which we have seen.
14351  UsageInfoMap UsageMap;
14352 
14353  /// The region we are currently within.
14354  SequenceTree::Seq Region;
14355 
14356  /// Filled in with declarations which were modified as a side-effect
14357  /// (that is, post-increment operations).
14358  SmallVectorImpl<std::pair<Object, Usage>> *ModAsSideEffect = nullptr;
14359 
14360  /// Expressions to check later. We defer checking these to reduce
14361  /// stack usage.
14362  SmallVectorImpl<const Expr *> &WorkList;
14363 
14364  /// RAII object wrapping the visitation of a sequenced subexpression of an
14365  /// expression. At the end of this process, the side-effects of the evaluation
14366  /// become sequenced with respect to the value computation of the result, so
14367  /// we downgrade any UK_ModAsSideEffect within the evaluation to
14368  /// UK_ModAsValue.
14369  struct SequencedSubexpression {
14370  SequencedSubexpression(SequenceChecker &Self)
14371  : Self(Self), OldModAsSideEffect(Self.ModAsSideEffect) {
14372  Self.ModAsSideEffect = &ModAsSideEffect;
14373  }
14374 
14375  ~SequencedSubexpression() {
14376  for (const std::pair<Object, Usage> &M : llvm::reverse(ModAsSideEffect)) {
14377  // Add a new usage with usage kind UK_ModAsValue, and then restore
14378  // the previous usage with UK_ModAsSideEffect (thus clearing it if
14379  // the previous one was empty).
14380  UsageInfo &UI = Self.UsageMap[M.first];
14381  auto &SideEffectUsage = UI.Uses[UK_ModAsSideEffect];
14382  Self.addUsage(M.first, UI, SideEffectUsage.UsageExpr, UK_ModAsValue);
14383  SideEffectUsage = M.second;
14384  }
14385  Self.ModAsSideEffect = OldModAsSideEffect;
14386  }
14387 
14388  SequenceChecker &Self;
14389  SmallVector<std::pair<Object, Usage>, 4> ModAsSideEffect;
14390  SmallVectorImpl<std::pair<Object, Usage>> *OldModAsSideEffect;
14391  };
14392 
14393  /// RAII object wrapping the visitation of a subexpression which we might
14394  /// choose to evaluate as a constant. If any subexpression is evaluated and
14395  /// found to be non-constant, this allows us to suppress the evaluation of
14396  /// the outer expression.
14397  class EvaluationTracker {
14398  public:
14399  EvaluationTracker(SequenceChecker &Self)
14400  : Self(Self), Prev(Self.EvalTracker) {
14401  Self.EvalTracker = this;
14402  }
14403 
14404  ~EvaluationTracker() {
14405  Self.EvalTracker = Prev;
14406  if (Prev)
14407  Prev->EvalOK &= EvalOK;
14408  }
14409 
14410  bool evaluate(const Expr *E, bool &Result) {
14411  if (!EvalOK || E->isValueDependent())
14412  return false;
14413  EvalOK = E->EvaluateAsBooleanCondition(
14414  Result, Self.SemaRef.Context, Self.SemaRef.isConstantEvaluated());
14415  return EvalOK;
14416  }
14417 
14418  private:
14419  SequenceChecker &Self;
14420  EvaluationTracker *Prev;
14421  bool EvalOK = true;
14422  } *EvalTracker = nullptr;
14423 
14424  /// Find the object which is produced by the specified expression,
14425  /// if any.
14426  Object getObject(const Expr *E, bool Mod) const {
14427  E = E->IgnoreParenCasts();
14428  if (const UnaryOperator *UO = dyn_cast<UnaryOperator>(E)) {
14429  if (Mod && (UO->getOpcode() == UO_PreInc || UO->getOpcode() == UO_PreDec))
14430  return getObject(UO->getSubExpr(), Mod);
14431  } else if (const BinaryOperator *BO = dyn_cast<BinaryOperator>(E)) {
14432  if (BO->getOpcode() == BO_Comma)
14433  return getObject(BO->getRHS(), Mod);
14434  if (Mod && BO->isAssignmentOp())
14435  return getObject(BO->getLHS(), Mod);
14436  } else if (const MemberExpr *ME = dyn_cast<MemberExpr>(E)) {
14437  // FIXME: Check for more interesting cases, like "x.n = ++x.n".
14438  if (isa<CXXThisExpr>(ME->getBase()->IgnoreParenCasts()))
14439  return ME->getMemberDecl();
14440  } else if (const DeclRefExpr *DRE = dyn_cast<DeclRefExpr>(E))
14441  // FIXME: If this is a reference, map through to its value.
14442  return DRE->getDecl();
14443  return nullptr;
14444  }
14445 
14446  /// Note that an object \p O was modified or used by an expression
14447  /// \p UsageExpr with usage kind \p UK. \p UI is the \p UsageInfo for
14448  /// the object \p O as obtained via the \p UsageMap.
14449  void addUsage(Object O, UsageInfo &UI, const Expr *UsageExpr, UsageKind UK) {
14450  // Get the old usage for the given object and usage kind.
14451  Usage &U = UI.Uses[UK];
14452  if (!U.UsageExpr || !Tree.isUnsequenced(Region, U.Seq)) {
14453  // If we have a modification as side effect and are in a sequenced
14454  // subexpression, save the old Usage so that we can restore it later
14455  // in SequencedSubexpression::~SequencedSubexpression.
14456  if (UK == UK_ModAsSideEffect && ModAsSideEffect)
14457  ModAsSideEffect->push_back(std::make_pair(O, U));
14458  // Then record the new usage with the current sequencing region.
14459  U.UsageExpr = UsageExpr;
14460  U.Seq = Region;
14461  }
14462  }
14463 
14464  /// Check whether a modification or use of an object \p O in an expression
14465  /// \p UsageExpr conflicts with a prior usage of kind \p OtherKind. \p UI is
14466  /// the \p UsageInfo for the object \p O as obtained via the \p UsageMap.
14467  /// \p IsModMod is true when we are checking for a mod-mod unsequenced
14468  /// usage and false we are checking for a mod-use unsequenced usage.
14469  void checkUsage(Object O, UsageInfo &UI, const Expr *UsageExpr,
14470  UsageKind OtherKind, bool IsModMod) {
14471  if (UI.Diagnosed)
14472  return;
14473 
14474  const Usage &U = UI.Uses[OtherKind];
14475  if (!U.UsageExpr || !Tree.isUnsequenced(Region, U.Seq))
14476  return;
14477 
14478  const Expr *Mod = U.UsageExpr;
14479  const Expr *ModOrUse = UsageExpr;
14480  if (OtherKind == UK_Use)
14481  std::swap(Mod, ModOrUse);
14482 
14483  SemaRef.DiagRuntimeBehavior(
14484  Mod->getExprLoc(), {Mod, ModOrUse},
14485  SemaRef.PDiag(IsModMod ? diag::warn_unsequenced_mod_mod
14486  : diag::warn_unsequenced_mod_use)
14487  << O << SourceRange(ModOrUse->getExprLoc()));
14488  UI.Diagnosed = true;
14489  }
14490 
14491  // A note on note{Pre, Post}{Use, Mod}:
14492  //
14493  // (It helps to follow the algorithm with an expression such as
14494  // "((++k)++, k) = k" or "k = (k++, k++)". Both contain unsequenced
14495  // operations before C++17 and both are well-defined in C++17).
14496  //
14497  // When visiting a node which uses/modify an object we first call notePreUse
14498  // or notePreMod before visiting its sub-expression(s). At this point the
14499  // children of the current node have not yet been visited and so the eventual
14500  // uses/modifications resulting from the children of the current node have not
14501  // been recorded yet.
14502  //
14503  // We then visit the children of the current node. After that notePostUse or
14504  // notePostMod is called. These will 1) detect an unsequenced modification
14505  // as side effect (as in "k++ + k") and 2) add a new usage with the
14506  // appropriate usage kind.
14507  //
14508  // We also have to be careful that some operation sequences modification as
14509  // side effect as well (for example: || or ,). To account for this we wrap
14510  // the visitation of such a sub-expression (for example: the LHS of || or ,)
14511  // with SequencedSubexpression. SequencedSubexpression is an RAII object
14512  // which record usages which are modifications as side effect, and then
14513  // downgrade them (or more accurately restore the previous usage which was a
14514  // modification as side effect) when exiting the scope of the sequenced
14515  // subexpression.
14516 
14517  void notePreUse(Object O, const Expr *UseExpr) {
14518  UsageInfo &UI = UsageMap[O];
14519  // Uses conflict with other modifications.
14520  checkUsage(O, UI, UseExpr, /*OtherKind=*/UK_ModAsValue, /*IsModMod=*/false);
14521  }
14522 
14523  void notePostUse(Object O, const Expr *UseExpr) {
14524  UsageInfo &UI = UsageMap[O];
14525  checkUsage(O, UI, UseExpr, /*OtherKind=*/UK_ModAsSideEffect,
14526  /*IsModMod=*/false);
14527  addUsage(O, UI, UseExpr, /*UsageKind=*/UK_Use);
14528  }
14529 
14530  void notePreMod(Object O, const Expr *ModExpr) {
14531  UsageInfo &UI = UsageMap[O];
14532  // Modifications conflict with other modifications and with uses.
14533  checkUsage(O, UI, ModExpr, /*OtherKind=*/UK_ModAsValue, /*IsModMod=*/true);
14534  checkUsage(O, UI, ModExpr, /*OtherKind=*/UK_Use, /*IsModMod=*/false);
14535  }
14536 
14537  void notePostMod(Object O, const Expr *ModExpr, UsageKind UK) {
14538  UsageInfo &UI = UsageMap[O];
14539  checkUsage(O, UI, ModExpr, /*OtherKind=*/UK_ModAsSideEffect,
14540  /*IsModMod=*/true);
14541  addUsage(O, UI, ModExpr, /*UsageKind=*/UK);
14542  }
14543 
14544 public:
14545  SequenceChecker(Sema &S, const Expr *E,
14546  SmallVectorImpl<const Expr *> &WorkList)
14547  : Base(S.Context), SemaRef(S), Region(Tree.root()), WorkList(WorkList) {
14548  Visit(E);
14549  // Silence a -Wunused-private-field since WorkList is now unused.
14550  // TODO: Evaluate if it can be used, and if not remove it.
14551  (void)this->WorkList;
14552  }
14553 
14554  void VisitStmt(const Stmt *S) {
14555  // Skip all statements which aren't expressions for now.
14556  }
14557 
14558  void VisitExpr(const Expr *E) {
14559  // By default, just recurse to evaluated subexpressions.
14560  Base::VisitStmt(E);
14561  }
14562 
14563  void VisitCastExpr(const CastExpr *E) {
14564  Object O = Object();
14565  if (E->getCastKind() == CK_LValueToRValue)
14566  O = getObject(E->getSubExpr(), false);
14567 
14568  if (O)
14569  notePreUse(O, E);
14570  VisitExpr(E);
14571  if (O)
14572  notePostUse(O, E);
14573  }
14574 
14575  void VisitSequencedExpressions(const Expr *SequencedBefore,
14576  const Expr *SequencedAfter) {
14577  SequenceTree::Seq BeforeRegion = Tree.allocate(Region);
14578  SequenceTree::Seq AfterRegion = Tree.allocate(Region);
14579  SequenceTree::Seq OldRegion = Region;
14580 
14581  {
14582  SequencedSubexpression SeqBefore(*this);
14583  Region = BeforeRegion;
14584  Visit(SequencedBefore);
14585  }
14586 
14587  Region = AfterRegion;
14588  Visit(SequencedAfter);
14589 
14590  Region = OldRegion;
14591 
14592  Tree.merge(BeforeRegion);
14593  Tree.merge(AfterRegion);
14594  }
14595 
14596  void VisitArraySubscriptExpr(const ArraySubscriptExpr *ASE) {
14597  // C++17 [expr.sub]p1:
14598  // The expression E1[E2] is identical (by definition) to *((E1)+(E2)). The
14599  // expression E1 is sequenced before the expression E2.
14600  if (SemaRef.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus17)
14601  VisitSequencedExpressions(ASE->getLHS(), ASE->getRHS());
14602  else {
14603  Visit(ASE->getLHS());
14604  Visit(ASE->getRHS());
14605  }
14606  }
14607 
14608  void VisitBinPtrMemD(const BinaryOperator *BO) { VisitBinPtrMem(BO); }
14609  void VisitBinPtrMemI(const BinaryOperator *BO) { VisitBinPtrMem(BO); }
14610  void VisitBinPtrMem(const BinaryOperator *BO) {
14611  // C++17 [expr.mptr.oper]p4:
14612  // Abbreviating pm-expression.*cast-expression as E1.*E2, [...]
14613  // the expression E1 is sequenced before the expression E2.
14614  if (SemaRef.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus17)
14615  VisitSequencedExpressions(BO->getLHS(), BO->getRHS());
14616  else {
14617  Visit(BO->getLHS());
14618  Visit(BO->getRHS());
14619  }
14620  }
14621 
14622  void VisitBinShl(const BinaryOperator *BO) { VisitBinShlShr(BO); }
14623  void VisitBinShr(const BinaryOperator *BO) { VisitBinShlShr(BO); }
14624  void VisitBinShlShr(const BinaryOperator *BO) {
14625  // C++17 [expr.shift]p4:
14626  // The expression E1 is sequenced before the expression E2.
14627  if (SemaRef.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus17)
14628  VisitSequencedExpressions(BO->getLHS(), BO->getRHS());
14629  else {
14630  Visit(BO->getLHS());
14631  Visit(BO->getRHS());
14632  }
14633  }
14634 
14635  void VisitBinComma(const BinaryOperator *BO) {
14636  // C++11 [expr.comma]p1:
14637  // Every value computation and side effect associated with the left
14638  // expression is sequenced before every value computation and side
14639  // effect associated with the right expression.
14640  VisitSequencedExpressions(BO->getLHS(), BO->getRHS());
14641  }
14642 
14643  void VisitBinAssign(const BinaryOperator *BO) {
14644  SequenceTree::Seq RHSRegion;
14645  SequenceTree::Seq LHSRegion;
14646  if (SemaRef.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus17) {
14647  RHSRegion = Tree.allocate(Region);
14648  LHSRegion = Tree.allocate(Region);
14649  } else {
14650  RHSRegion = Region;
14651  LHSRegion = Region;
14652  }
14653  SequenceTree::Seq OldRegion = Region;
14654 
14655  // C++11 [expr.ass]p1:
14656  // [...] the assignment is sequenced after the value computation
14657  // of the right and left operands, [...]
14658  //
14659  // so check it before inspecting the operands and update the
14660  // map afterwards.
14661  Object O = getObject(BO->getLHS(), /*Mod=*/true);
14662  if (O)
14663  notePreMod(O, BO);
14664 
14665  if (SemaRef.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus17) {
14666  // C++17 [expr.ass]p1:
14667  // [...] The right operand is sequenced before the left operand. [...]
14668  {
14669  SequencedSubexpression SeqBefore(*this);
14670  Region = RHSRegion;
14671  Visit(BO->getRHS());
14672  }
14673 
14674  Region = LHSRegion;
14675  Visit(BO->getLHS());
14676 
14677  if (O && isa<CompoundAssignOperator>(BO))
14678  notePostUse(O, BO);
14679 
14680  } else {
14681  // C++11 does not specify any sequencing between the LHS and RHS.
14682  Region = LHSRegion;
14683  Visit(BO->getLHS());
14684 
14685  if (O && isa<CompoundAssignOperator>(BO))
14686  notePostUse(O, BO);
14687 
14688  Region = RHSRegion;
14689  Visit(BO->getRHS());
14690  }
14691 
14692  // C++11 [expr.ass]p1:
14693  // the assignment is sequenced [...] before the value computation of the
14694  // assignment expression.
14695  // C11 6.5.16/3 has no such rule.
14696  Region = OldRegion;
14697  if (O)
14698  notePostMod(O, BO,
14699  SemaRef.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus ? UK_ModAsValue
14700  : UK_ModAsSideEffect);
14701  if (SemaRef.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus17) {
14702  Tree.merge(RHSRegion);
14703  Tree.merge(LHSRegion);
14704  }
14705  }
14706 
14707  void VisitCompoundAssignOperator(const CompoundAssignOperator *CAO) {
14708  VisitBinAssign(CAO);
14709  }
14710 
14711  void VisitUnaryPreInc(const UnaryOperator *UO) { VisitUnaryPreIncDec(UO); }
14712  void VisitUnaryPreDec(const UnaryOperator *UO) { VisitUnaryPreIncDec(UO); }
14713  void VisitUnaryPreIncDec(const UnaryOperator *UO) {
14714  Object O = getObject(UO->getSubExpr(), true);
14715  if (!O)
14716  return VisitExpr(UO);
14717 
14718  notePreMod(O, UO);
14719  Visit(UO->getSubExpr());
14720  // C++11 [expr.pre.incr]p1:
14721  // the expression ++x is equivalent to x+=1
14722  notePostMod(O, UO,
14723  SemaRef.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus ? UK_ModAsValue
14724  : UK_ModAsSideEffect);
14725  }
14726 
14727  void VisitUnaryPostInc(const UnaryOperator *UO) { VisitUnaryPostIncDec(UO); }
14728  void VisitUnaryPostDec(const UnaryOperator *UO) { VisitUnaryPostIncDec(UO); }
14729  void VisitUnaryPostIncDec(const UnaryOperator *UO) {
14730  Object O = getObject(UO->getSubExpr(), true);
14731  if (!O)
14732  return VisitExpr(UO);
14733 
14734  notePreMod(O, UO);
14735  Visit(UO->getSubExpr());
14736  notePostMod(O, UO, UK_ModAsSideEffect);
14737  }
14738 
14739  void VisitBinLOr(const BinaryOperator *BO) {
14740  // C++11 [expr.log.or]p2:
14741  // If the second expression is evaluated, every value computation and
14742  // side effect associated with the first expression is sequenced before
14743  // every value computation and side effect associated with the
14744  // second expression.
14745  SequenceTree::Seq LHSRegion = Tree.allocate(Region);
14746  SequenceTree::Seq RHSRegion = Tree.allocate(Region);
14747  SequenceTree::Seq OldRegion = Region;
14748 
14749  EvaluationTracker Eval(*this);
14750  {
14751  SequencedSubexpression Sequenced(*this);
14752  Region = LHSRegion;
14753  Visit(BO->getLHS());
14754  }
14755 
14756  // C++11 [expr.log.or]p1:
14757  // [...] the second operand is not evaluated if the first operand
14758  // evaluates to true.
14759  bool EvalResult = false;
14760  bool EvalOK = Eval.evaluate(BO->getLHS(), EvalResult);
14761  bool ShouldVisitRHS = !EvalOK || (EvalOK && !EvalResult);
14762  if (ShouldVisitRHS) {
14763  Region = RHSRegion;
14764  Visit(BO->getRHS());
14765  }
14766 
14767  Region = OldRegion;
14768  Tree.merge(LHSRegion);
14769  Tree.merge(RHSRegion);
14770  }
14771 
14772  void VisitBinLAnd(const BinaryOperator *BO) {
14773  // C++11 [expr.log.and]p2:
14774  // If the second expression is evaluated, every value computation and
14775  // side effect associated with the first expression is sequenced before
14776  // every value computation and side effect associated with the
14777  // second expression.
14778  SequenceTree::Seq LHSRegion = Tree.allocate(Region);
14779  SequenceTree::Seq RHSRegion = Tree.allocate(Region);
14780  SequenceTree::Seq OldRegion = Region;
14781 
14782  EvaluationTracker Eval(*this);
14783  {
14784  SequencedSubexpression Sequenced(*this);
14785  Region = LHSRegion;
14786  Visit(BO->getLHS());
14787  }
14788 
14789  // C++11 [expr.log.and]p1:
14790  // [...] the second operand is not evaluated if the first operand is false.
14791  bool EvalResult = false;
14792  bool EvalOK = Eval.evaluate(BO->getLHS(), EvalResult);
14793  bool ShouldVisitRHS = !EvalOK || (EvalOK && EvalResult);
14794  if (ShouldVisitRHS) {
14795  Region = RHSRegion;
14796  Visit(BO->getRHS());
14797  }
14798 
14799  Region = OldRegion;
14800  Tree.merge(LHSRegion);
14801  Tree.merge(RHSRegion);
14802  }
14803 
14804  void VisitAbstractConditionalOperator(const AbstractConditionalOperator *CO) {
14805  // C++11 [expr.cond]p1:
14806  // [...] Every value computation and side effect associated with the first
14807  // expression is sequenced before every value computation and side effect
14808  // associated with the second or third expression.
14809  SequenceTree::Seq ConditionRegion = Tree.allocate(Region);
14810 
14811  // No sequencing is specified between the true and false expression.
14812  // However since exactly one of both is going to be evaluated we can
14813  // consider them to be sequenced. This is needed to avoid warning on
14814  // something like "x ? y+= 1 : y += 2;" in the case where we will visit
14815  // both the true and false expressions because we can't evaluate x.
14816  // This will still allow us to detect an expression like (pre C++17)
14817  // "(x ? y += 1 : y += 2) = y".
14818  //
14819  // We don't wrap the visitation of the true and false expression with
14820  // SequencedSubexpression because we don't want to downgrade modifications
14821  // as side effect in the true and false expressions after the visition
14822  // is done. (for example in the expression "(x ? y++ : y++) + y" we should
14823  // not warn between the two "y++", but we should warn between the "y++"
14824  // and the "y".
14825  SequenceTree::Seq TrueRegion = Tree.allocate(Region);
14826  SequenceTree::Seq FalseRegion = Tree.allocate(Region);
14827  SequenceTree::Seq OldRegion = Region;
14828 
14829  EvaluationTracker Eval(*this);
14830  {
14831  SequencedSubexpression Sequenced(*this);
14832  Region = ConditionRegion;
14833  Visit(CO->getCond());
14834  }
14835 
14836  // C++11 [expr.cond]p1:
14837  // [...] The first expression is contextually converted to bool (Clause 4).
14838  // It is evaluated and if it is true, the result of the conditional
14839  // expression is the value of the second expression, otherwise that of the
14840  // third expression. Only one of the second and third expressions is
14841  // evaluated. [...]
14842  bool EvalResult = false;
14843  bool EvalOK = Eval.evaluate(CO->getCond(), EvalResult);
14844  bool ShouldVisitTrueExpr = !EvalOK || (EvalOK && EvalResult);
14845  bool ShouldVisitFalseExpr = !EvalOK || (EvalOK && !EvalResult);
14846  if (ShouldVisitTrueExpr) {
14847  Region = TrueRegion;
14848  Visit(CO->getTrueExpr());
14849  }
14850  if (ShouldVisitFalseExpr) {
14851  Region = FalseRegion;
14852  Visit(CO->getFalseExpr());
14853  }
14854 
14855  Region = OldRegion;
14856  Tree.merge(ConditionRegion);
14857  Tree.merge(TrueRegion);
14858  Tree.merge(FalseRegion);
14859  }
14860 
14861  void VisitCallExpr(const CallExpr *CE) {
14862  // FIXME: CXXNewExpr and CXXDeleteExpr implicitly call functions.
14863 
14864  if (CE->isUnevaluatedBuiltinCall(Context))
14865  return;
14866 
14867  // C++11 [intro.execution]p15:
14868  // When calling a function [...], every value computation and side effect
14869  // associated with any argument expression, or with the postfix expression
14870  // designating the called function, is sequenced before execution of every
14871  // expression or statement in the body of the function [and thus before
14872  // the value computation of its result].
14873  SequencedSubexpression Sequenced(*this);
14874  SemaRef.runWithSufficientStackSpace(CE->getExprLoc(), [&] {
14875  // C++17 [expr.call]p5
14876  // The postfix-expression is sequenced before each expression in the
14877  // expression-list and any default argument. [...]
14878  SequenceTree::Seq CalleeRegion;
14879  SequenceTree::Seq OtherRegion;
14880  if (SemaRef.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus17) {
14881  CalleeRegion = Tree.allocate(Region);
14882  OtherRegion = Tree.allocate(Region);
14883  } else {
14884  CalleeRegion = Region;
14885  OtherRegion = Region;
14886  }
14887  SequenceTree::Seq OldRegion = Region;
14888 
14889  // Visit the callee expression first.
14890  Region = CalleeRegion;
14891  if (SemaRef.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus17) {
14892  SequencedSubexpression Sequenced(*this);
14893  Visit(CE->getCallee());
14894  } else {
14895  Visit(CE->getCallee());
14896  }
14897 
14898  // Then visit the argument expressions.
14899  Region = OtherRegion;
14900  for (const Expr *Argument : CE->arguments())
14901  Visit(Argument);
14902 
14903  Region = OldRegion;
14904  if (SemaRef.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus17) {
14905  Tree.merge(CalleeRegion);
14906  Tree.merge(OtherRegion);
14907  }
14908  });
14909  }
14910 
14911  void VisitCXXOperatorCallExpr(const CXXOperatorCallExpr *CXXOCE) {
14912  // C++17 [over.match.oper]p2:
14913  // [...] the operator notation is first transformed to the equivalent
14914  // function-call notation as summarized in Table 12 (where @ denotes one
14915  // of the operators covered in the specified subclause). However, the
14916  // operands are sequenced in the order prescribed for the built-in
14917  // operator (Clause 8).
14918  //
14919  // From the above only overloaded binary operators and overloaded call
14920  // operators have sequencing rules in C++17 that we need to handle
14921  // separately.
14922  if (!SemaRef.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus17 ||
14923  (CXXOCE->getNumArgs() != 2 && CXXOCE->getOperator() != OO_Call))
14924  return VisitCallExpr(CXXOCE);
14925 
14926  enum {
14927  NoSequencing,
14928  LHSBeforeRHS,
14929  RHSBeforeLHS,
14930  LHSBeforeRest
14931  } SequencingKind;
14932  switch (CXXOCE->getOperator()) {
14933  case OO_Equal:
14934  case OO_PlusEqual:
14935  case OO_MinusEqual:
14936  case OO_StarEqual:
14937  case OO_SlashEqual:
14938  case OO_PercentEqual:
14939  case OO_CaretEqual:
14940  case OO_AmpEqual:
14941  case OO_PipeEqual:
14942  case OO_LessLessEqual:
14943  case OO_GreaterGreaterEqual:
14944  SequencingKind = RHSBeforeLHS;
14945  break;
14946 
14947  case OO_LessLess:
14948  case OO_GreaterGreater:
14949  case OO_AmpAmp:
14950  case OO_PipePipe:
14951  case OO_Comma:
14952  case OO_ArrowStar:
14953  case OO_Subscript:
14954  SequencingKind = LHSBeforeRHS;
14955  break;
14956 
14957  case OO_Call:
14958  SequencingKind = LHSBeforeRest;
14959  break;
14960 
14961  default:
14962  SequencingKind = NoSequencing;
14963  break;
14964  }
14965 
14966  if (SequencingKind == NoSequencing)
14967  return VisitCallExpr(CXXOCE);
14968 
14969  // This is a call, so all subexpressions are sequenced before the result.
14970  SequencedSubexpression Sequenced(*this);
14971 
14972  SemaRef.runWithSufficientStackSpace(CXXOCE->getExprLoc(), [&] {
14973  assert(SemaRef.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus17 &&
14974  "Should only get there with C++17 and above!");
14975  assert((CXXOCE->getNumArgs() == 2 || CXXOCE->getOperator() == OO_Call) &&
14976  "Should only get there with an overloaded binary operator"
14977  " or an overloaded call operator!");
14978 
14979  if (SequencingKind == LHSBeforeRest) {
14980  assert(CXXOCE->getOperator() == OO_Call &&
14981  "We should only have an overloaded call operator here!");
14982 
14983  // This is very similar to VisitCallExpr, except that we only have the
14984  // C++17 case. The postfix-expression is the first argument of the
14985  // CXXOperatorCallExpr. The expressions in the expression-list, if any,
14986  // are in the following arguments.
14987  //
14988  // Note that we intentionally do not visit the callee expression since
14989  // it is just a decayed reference to a function.
14990  SequenceTree::Seq PostfixExprRegion = Tree.allocate(Region);
14991  SequenceTree::Seq ArgsRegion = Tree.allocate(Region);
14992  SequenceTree::Seq OldRegion = Region;
14993 
14994  assert(CXXOCE->getNumArgs() >= 1 &&
14995  "An overloaded call operator must have at least one argument"
14996  " for the postfix-expression!");
14997  const Expr *PostfixExpr = CXXOCE->getArgs()[0];
14998  llvm::ArrayRef<const Expr *> Args(CXXOCE->getArgs() + 1,
14999  CXXOCE->getNumArgs() - 1);
15000 
15001  // Visit the postfix-expression first.
15002  {
15003  Region = PostfixExprRegion;
15004  SequencedSubexpression Sequenced(*this);
15005  Visit(PostfixExpr);
15006  }
15007 
15008  // Then visit the argument expressions.
15009  Region = ArgsRegion;
15010  for (const Expr *Arg : Args)
15011  Visit(Arg);
15012 
15013  Region = OldRegion;
15014  Tree.merge(PostfixExprRegion);
15015  Tree.merge(ArgsRegion);
15016  } else {
15017  assert(CXXOCE->getNumArgs() == 2 &&
15018  "Should only have two arguments here!");
15019  assert((SequencingKind == LHSBeforeRHS ||
15020  SequencingKind == RHSBeforeLHS) &&
15021  "Unexpected sequencing kind!");
15022 
15023  // We do not visit the callee expression since it is just a decayed
15024  // reference to a function.
15025  const Expr *E1 = CXXOCE->getArg(0);
15026  const Expr *E2 = CXXOCE->getArg(1);
15027  if (SequencingKind == RHSBeforeLHS)
15028  std::swap(E1, E2);
15029 
15030  return VisitSequencedExpressions(E1, E2);
15031  }
15032  });
15033  }
15034 
15035  void VisitCXXConstructExpr(const CXXConstructExpr *CCE) {
15036  // This is a call, so all subexpressions are sequenced before the result.
15037  SequencedSubexpression Sequenced(*this);
15038 
15039  if (!CCE->isListInitialization())
15040  return VisitExpr(CCE);
15041 
15042  // In C++11, list initializations are sequenced.
15043  SmallVector<SequenceTree::Seq, 32> Elts;
15044  SequenceTree::Seq Parent = Region;
15045  for (CXXConstructExpr::const_arg_iterator I = CCE->arg_begin(),
15046  E = CCE->arg_end();
15047  I != E; ++I) {
15048  Region = Tree.allocate(Parent);
15049  Elts.push_back(Region);
15050  Visit(*I);
15051  }
15052 
15053  // Forget that the initializers are sequenced.
15054  Region = Parent;
15055  for (unsigned I = 0; I < Elts.size(); ++I)
15056  Tree.merge(Elts[I]);
15057  }
15058 
15059  void VisitInitListExpr(const InitListExpr *ILE) {
15060  if (!SemaRef.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus11)
15061  return VisitExpr(ILE);
15062 
15063  // In C++11, list initializations are sequenced.
15064  SmallVector<SequenceTree::Seq, 32> Elts;
15065  SequenceTree::Seq Parent = Region;
15066  for (unsigned I = 0; I < ILE->getNumInits(); ++I) {
15067  const Expr *E = ILE->getInit(I);
15068  if (!E)
15069  continue;
15070  Region = Tree.allocate(Parent);
15071  Elts.push_back(Region);
15072  Visit(E);
15073  }
15074 
15075  // Forget that the initializers are sequenced.
15076  Region = Parent;
15077  for (unsigned I = 0; I < Elts.size(); ++I)
15078  Tree.merge(Elts[I]);
15079  }
15080 };
15081 
15082 } // namespace

15084 void Sema::CheckUnsequencedOperations(const Expr *E) {
15085  SmallVector<const Expr *, 8> WorkList;
15086  WorkList.push_back(E);
15087  while (!WorkList.empty()) {
15088  const Expr *Item = WorkList.pop_back_val();
15089  SequenceChecker(*this, Item, WorkList);
15090  }
15091 }

15093 void Sema::CheckCompletedExpr(Expr *E, SourceLocation CheckLoc,
15094  bool IsConstexpr) {
15095  llvm::SaveAndRestore<bool> ConstantContext(
15096  isConstantEvaluatedOverride, IsConstexpr || isa<ConstantExpr>(E));
15097  CheckImplicitConversions(E, CheckLoc);
15098  if (!E->isInstantiationDependent())
15099  CheckUnsequencedOperations(E);
15100  if (!IsConstexpr && !E->isValueDependent())
15101  CheckForIntOverflow(E);
15102  DiagnoseMisalignedMembers();
15103 }
